# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The **American Civil War** (April 12, 1861 – May 26, 1865; also known by other names) was a civil war in the United States between the Union ("the North") and the Confederacy ("the South"), which was formed in 1861 by states that had seceded from the Union to preserve slavery in the United States.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The South saw slavery as threatened because of the election of Abraham Lincoln and the growing abolitionist movement in the North.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The war ended with Union victory, the dissolution of the Confederacy and the abolition of slavery, freeing four million African Americans.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Decades of controversy over slavery came to a head when Abraham Lincoln, a Republican who opposed slavery's expansion, won the 1860 presidential election.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Seven slave states in the South responded to Lincoln's victory by seceding from the United States and forming the Confederate States of America.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy seized US forts and other federal assets in the South.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The war began on April 12, 1861, when the Confederacy bombarded Fort Sumter in South Carolina.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] A wave of enthusiasm for war swept over the North and South, as military recruitment soared.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Four more Southern states seceded after the war began and, led by its president, Jefferson Davis, the Confederacy comprised eleven states, containing a third of the US population.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Four years of intense combat, mostly in the South, ensued.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] During 1861–1862 in the western theater, the Union made permanent gains, though in the eastern theater the conflict was inconclusive.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The abolition of slavery became a Union war goal on January 1, 1863, when Lincoln issued the Emancipation Proclamation, which declared all slaves in rebel states to be free, applying to more than 3.5 million of the 4 million enslaved people in the country.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] To the west, the Union first destroyed the Confederacy's river navy by the summer of 1862, then much of its western armies, and seized New Orleans.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The successful 1863 Union siege of Vicksburg split the Confederacy in two at the Mississippi River, while Confederate general Robert E.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Lee's incursion north failed at the Battle of Gettysburg.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Grant's western successes led Lincoln to promote him to command of all Union armies in 1864.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Inflicting an ever-tightening naval blockade of Confederate ports, the Union marshaled resources and manpower to attack the Confederacy from all directions.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] This led to the fall of Atlanta in 1864 to Union general William Tecumseh Sherman, followed by his March to the Sea, which culminated in his taking Savannah.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The last significant battles raged around the ten-month Siege of Petersburg, gateway to the Confederate capital of Richmond.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederates abandoned Richmond, and on April 9, 1865, Lee surrendered to Grant following the Battle of Appomattox Court House, setting in motion the end of the war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln lived to see this victory but was shot by an assassin on April 14, dying the next day.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] By the end of the war, much of the South's infrastructure had been destroyed.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy collapsed, the Thirteenth Amendment abolished slavery, and four million enslaved black people were freed.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The war-torn nation then entered the Reconstruction era in an attempt to rebuild the country, bring the former Confederate states back into the United States, and grant civil rights to freed slaves.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The war is one of the most extensively studied and written about episodes in the history of the United States.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] It remains the subject of cultural and historiographical debate.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Of continuing interest is the myth of the Lost Cause of the Confederacy.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The war was among the first to use industrial warfare.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Railroads, the electrical telegraph, steamships, the ironclad warship, and mass-produced weapons were widely used.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The war left an estimated 700,000 soldiers dead, along with an undetermined number of civilian deaths, making it the deadliest in American history.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The technology and brutality of the Civil War foreshadowed the coming world wars.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The origins of the war were rooted in the desire of the Southern states to preserve the institution of slavery.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Historians in the 21st century overwhelmingly agree on the centrality of slavery in the conflict—at least for the Southern states.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] They disagree on the North's reasons for refusing to allow the Southern states to secede.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The pseudo-historical Lost Cause ideology denies that slavery was the principal cause of the secession, a view disproven by historical evidence, including the seceding states' own secession documents.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The principal political battle leading to Southern secession was over whether slavery would expand into the Western territories destined to become states.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Initially Congress had admitted new states into the Union in pairs, one slave and one free.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] This had kept a sectional balance in the Senate but not in the House of Representatives, as free states outstripped slave states in numbers of eligible voters.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Thus, at mid-19th century, the free-versus-slave status of the new territories was a critical issue, both for the North, where anti-slavery sentiment had grown, and for the South, where the fear of slavery's abolition had grown.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Another factor leading to secession and the formation of the Confederacy was the development of white Southern nationalism in the preceding decades.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The primary reason for the North to reject secession was to preserve the Union, a cause based on American nationalism.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Background factors in the run up to the Civil War were partisan politics, abolitionism, nullification versus secession, Southern and Northern nationalism, expansionism, economics, and modernization in the antebellum period.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Abraham Lincoln won the 1860 presidential election.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Southern leaders feared Lincoln would stop slavery's expansion and put it on a course toward extinction.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] His victory triggered declarations of secession by seven slave states of the Deep South, all of whose riverfront or coastal economies were based on cotton that was cultivated by slave labor.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln was not inaugurated until March 4, 1861, four months after his 1860 election, which afforded the South time to prepare for war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Nationalists in the North and "Unionists" in the South refused to accept the declarations of secession, and no foreign government ever recognized the Confederacy.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The US government, under President James Buchanan, refused to relinquish the nation's forts, which the Confederacy claimed were located in their territory.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] According to Lincoln, the American people had demonstrated, beginning with their victory in the American Revolution and Revolutionary War and subsequent establishment of a sovereign nation, that they could successfully establish and administer a republic.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Yet, Lincoln believed, a question remained unanswered: Could the nation be maintained as a republic, with its government selected by vote of the people, in the face of internal attempts to destroy it or separate from it?
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln's election provoked South Carolina's legislature to call a state convention to consider secession.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] South Carolina had done more than any other state to advance the notion that a state had the right to nullify federal laws and even secede.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] On December 20, 1860, the convention unanimously voted to secede and adopted a secession declaration.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] It argued for states' rights for slave owners but complained about states' rights in the North in the form of resistance to the federal Fugitive Slave Act, claiming that Northern states were not fulfilling their obligations to assist in the return of fugitive slaves.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The "cotton states" of Mississippi, Florida, Alabama, Georgia, Louisiana, and Texas followed suit, seceding in January and February 1861.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Among the ordinances of secession, those of Texas, Alabama, and Virginia mentioned the plight of the "slaveholding states" at the hands of Northern abolitionists.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The rest made no mention of slavery but were brief announcements by the legislatures of the dissolution of ties to the Union.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] However, at least four—South Carolina, Mississippi, Georgia, and Texas—provided detailed reasons for their secession, all blaming the movement to abolish slavery and its influence over the North.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Southern states believed that the Fugitive Slave Clause made slaveholding a constitutional right.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] These states agreed to form a new federal government, the Confederate States of America, on February 4, 1861.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] They took control of federal forts and other properties within their boundaries, with little resistance from outgoing president James Buchanan, whose term ended on March 4.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Buchanan said the Dred Scott decision was proof the Southern states had no reason to secede and that the Union "was intended to be perpetual".
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] He added, however, that "The power by force of arms to compel a State to remain in the Union" was not among the "enumerated powers granted to Congress".
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] A quarter of the US army—the Texas garrison—was surrendered in February to state forces by its general, David E.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] West Virginia left the rest of Virginia and joined the Union as West Virginia because of the slavery issue.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] As Southerners resigned their Senate and House seats, Republicans could pass projects that had been blocked.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] These included the Morrill Tariff, land grant colleges, a Homestead Act, a transcontinental railroad, the National Bank Act, authorization of United States Notes by the Legal Tender Act of 1862, the end of slavery in the District of Columbia, and a ban on slavery in the territories.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The Revenue Act of 1861 introduced an income tax to help finance the war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] In December 1860, the Crittenden Compromise was proposed to re-establish the Missouri Compromise line, by constitutionally banning slavery in territories to the north of it, while permitting it to the south.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The Compromise would likely have prevented secession, but Lincoln and the Republicans rejected it.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln stated that any compromise that would extend slavery would bring down the Union.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] A February peace conference met in Washington, proposing a solution similar to the Compromise; it was rejected by Congress.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The Republicans proposed the Corwin Amendment, an alternative, not to interfere with slavery where it existed, but the South regarded it as insufficient.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The remaining eight slave states rejected pleas to join the Confederacy, following a no-vote in Virginia's First Secessionist Convention on April 4.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] On March 4, Lincoln was sworn in as president.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] In his first inaugural address, he argued that the Constitution was a *more perfect union* than the earlier Articles of Confederation and Perpetual Union, was a binding contract, and that secession was "legally void".
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] He did not intend to invade Southern states, nor to end slavery where it existed, but he said he would use force to maintain possession of federal property, including forts, arsenals, mints, and customhouses that had been seized.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] "The mails, unless repelled, will continue to be furnished in all parts of the Union." Where conditions did not allow peaceful enforcement of federal law, US marshals and judges would be withdrawn.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] No mention was made of bullion lost from mints.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] He stated that it would be US policy "to collect the duties and imposts"; "there will be no invasion, no using of force against or among the people anywhere" that would justify an armed revolution.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] His speech closed with a plea for restoration of the bonds of union, famously calling on "the mystic chords of memory" binding the two regions.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy sent delegates to Washington to negotiate a peace treaty.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln rejected negotiations, because he claimed that the Confederacy was not a legitimate government and to make a treaty with it would recognize it as such.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln instead attempted to negotiate directly with the governors of seceded states, whose administrations he continued to recognize.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Complicating Lincoln's attempts to defuse the crisis was Secretary of State William H.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Seward, who had been Lincoln's rival for the Republican nomination.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Embittered by his defeat, Seward agreed to support Lincoln's candidacy only after he was guaranteed the executive office then considered the second most powerful.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] In the early stages of Lincoln's presidency Seward held little regard for him, due to his perceived inexperience.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Seward viewed himself as the de facto head of government, the "prime minister" behind the throne.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Seward attempted to engage in unauthorized and indirect negotiations that failed.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln was determined to hold all remaining Union-occupied forts in the seceded states: Fort Pickens, Fort Jefferson, and Fort Taylor in Florida, and Fort Sumter in South Carolina.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The American Civil War began on April 12, 1861, when Confederate forces opened fire on the Union-held Fort Sumter.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Fort Sumter is located in the harbor of Charleston, South Carolina.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Its status had been contentious for months.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Outgoing president Buchanan had dithered in reinforcing its garrison, commanded by Major Robert Anderson.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Anderson took matters into his own hands and on December 26, 1860, under the cover of darkness, sailed the garrison from the poorly placed Fort Moultrie to the stalwart island Fort Sumter.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Anderson's actions catapulted him to hero status in the North.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] An attempt to resupply the fort on January 9, 1861, failed and nearly started the war then, but an informal truce held.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] On March 5, Lincoln was informed the fort was low on supplies.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Fort Sumter proved a key challenge to Lincoln's administration.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Back-channel dealing by Seward with the Confederates undermined Lincoln's decision-making; Seward wanted to pull out.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] But a firm hand by Lincoln tamed Seward, who was a staunch Lincoln ally thereafter.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln decided holding the fort, which would require reinforcing it, was the only workable option.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] On April 6, Lincoln informed the Governor of South Carolina that a ship with food but no ammunition would attempt to supply the fort.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] James McPherson describes this win-win approach as "the first sign of the mastery that would mark Lincoln's presidency"; the Union would win if it could resupply and hold the fort, and the South would be the aggressor if it opened fire on an unarmed ship supplying starving men.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] An April 9 Confederate cabinet meeting resulted in Davis ordering General P.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Beauregard to take the fort before supplies reached it.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] At 4:30 a.m. on April 12, Confederate forces fired the first of 4,000 shells at the fort; it fell the next day.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The loss of Fort Sumter lit a patriotic fire under the North.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] On April 15, Lincoln called on the states to field 75,000 militiamen for 90 days; impassioned Union states met the quotas quickly.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] On May 3, 1861, Lincoln called for an additional 42,000 volunteers for three years.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Shortly after this, Virginia, Tennessee, Arkansas, and North Carolina seceded and joined the Confederacy.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] To reward Virginia, the Confederate capital was moved to Richmond.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Maryland, Delaware, Missouri, and Kentucky, known as the border states, were slave states that had not seceded and whose people had divided loyalties to the North and South, with some men enlisting in the Union Army and others in the Confederate Army.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] West Virginia may be compared to the border states because it had slavery after it separated from Virginia and was admitted to the Union on June 20, 1863, but it was admitted under a plan of gradual emancipation known as the Willey Amendment.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Maryland's territory surrounded Washington, D.C., and could cut it off from the North.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] It had anti-Lincoln officials who tolerated anti-army rioting in Baltimore and the burning of bridges, both aimed at hindering the passage of troops to Washington, D.C., and the South.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Maryland's legislature voted overwhelmingly to stay in the Union, but rejected hostilities with its southern neighbors, voting to close Maryland's rail lines to prevent their use for war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln responded by establishing martial law and suspending habeas corpus in Maryland, along with sending in militia units.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] In *Ex parte Merryman*, Chief Justice Roger Taney found that only Congress could suspend habeas corpus, but Lincoln ignored his ruling.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln took control of Maryland and the District of Columbia by seizing prominent figures, including arresting one-third of the members of the Maryland General Assembly, who were pro-Confederate, on September 17, 1861, the day it intended to reconvene.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] All were held without trial at Fort McHenry in Baltimore.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] In September 1861, federal troops imprisoned a Baltimore newspaper editor, Frank Key Howard, after he criticized Lincoln in an editorial for ignoring Chief Justice Taney's ruling in *Ex parte Merryman*.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Howard wrote a book about his prison experiences, which was published early in 1863.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] It "stressed the crowded conditions and spartan hardships of prison life ... [and] likened the conditions in Fort Lafayette to those on 'a slave-ship, on the middle passage'".
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] In Missouri, an elected convention on secession voted to remain in the Union.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] When pro-Confederate Governor Claiborne Fox Jackson called out the state militia, it was attacked by federal forces under General Nathaniel Lyon, who chased the governor and rest of the State Guard to the southwestern corner of Missouri (see Missouri secession).
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Early in the war the Confederacy controlled southern Missouri through the Confederate government of Missouri but was driven out after 1862.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] In the resulting vacuum, the convention on secession reconvened and took power as the Unionist provisional government of Missouri.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Kentucky did not secede but declared itself neutral.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] When Confederate forces entered in September 1861, its neutrality ended and the state reaffirmed its Union status while maintaining slavery.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Its jurisdiction extended only as far as Confederate battle lines in the Commonwealth, which at its greatest extent was over half the state, and it went into exile after October 1862.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] After Virginia's secession, a Unionist government in Wheeling asked 48 counties to vote on an ordinance to create a new state in October 1861.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] A voter turnout of 34 percent approved the statehood bill (96 percent approving).
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Twenty-four secessionist counties were included in the new state, and the ensuing guerrilla war engaged about 40,000 federal troops for much of the war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Congress admitted West Virginia to the Union on June 20, 1863.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] West Virginians provided about 20,000 soldiers to each side in the war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] A Unionist secession attempt occurred in East Tennessee but was suppressed by the Confederacy, which arrested over 3,000 men suspected of loyalty to the Union; they were held without trial.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The Civil War was marked by intense and frequent battles.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Over four years, 237 named battles were fought, along with many smaller actions, often characterized by their bitter intensity and high casualties.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Historian John Keegan described it as "one of the most ferocious wars ever fought", where in many cases the only target was the enemy's soldiers.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] As the Confederate states organized, the US Army numbered 16,000, while Northern governors began mobilizing their militias.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederate Congress authorized up to 100,000 troops in February.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] By May, Jefferson Davis was pushing for another 100,000 soldiers for one year or the duration, and the US Congress responded in kind.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] In the first year of the war, both sides had more volunteers than they could effectively train and equip.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] After the initial enthusiasm faded, relying on young men who came of age each year was not enough.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Both sides enacted draft laws (conscription) to encourage or force volunteering, though relatively few were drafted.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy passed a draft law in April 1862 for men aged 18 to 35, with exemptions for overseers, government officials, and clergymen.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The US Congress followed in July, authorizing a militia draft within states that could not meet their quota with volunteers.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] European immigrants joined the Union Army in large numbers, including 177,000 born in Germany and 144,000 in Ireland.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] About 50,000 Canadians served, around 2,500 of whom were black.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] When the Emancipation Proclamation went into effect in January 1863, ex-slaves were energetically recruited to meet state quotas.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] States and local communities offered higher cash bonuses for white volunteers.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Congress tightened the draft law in March 1863.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Men selected in the draft could provide substitutes or, until mid-1864, pay commutation money.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Many eligibles pooled their money to cover the cost of anyone drafted.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Families used the substitute provision to select which man should go into the army and which should stay home.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] There was much evasion and resistance to the draft, especially in Catholic areas.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The New York City draft riots in July 1863 involved Irish immigrants who had been signed up as citizens to swell the vote of the city's Democratic political machine, not realizing it made them liable for the draft.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Of the 168,649 men procured for the Union through the draft, 117,986 were substitutes, leaving only 50,663 who were conscripted.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] In the North and South, draft laws were highly unpopular.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] In the North, some 120,000 men evaded conscription, many fleeing to Canada, and another 280,000 soldiers deserted during the war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] At least 100,000 Southerners deserted, about 10 percent of the total.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Southern desertion was high because many soldiers were more concerned about the fate of their local area than the Southern cause.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] In the North, "bounty jumpers" enlisted to collect the generous bonus, deserted, then re-enlisted under a different name for a second bonus; 141 were caught and executed.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] From a tiny frontier force in 1860, the Union and Confederate armies grew into the "largest and most efficient armies in the world" within a few years.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Some European observers at the time dismissed them as amateur and unprofessional, but historian John Keegan concluded that each outmatched the French, Prussian, and Russian armies, and without the Atlantic, could have threatened any of them with defeat.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Unionism was strong in certain areas within the Confederacy.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] As many as 100,000 men living in states under Confederate control served in the Union Army or pro-Union guerrilla groups.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Although they came from all classes, most Southern Unionists differed socially, culturally, and economically from their region's dominant prewar, slave-owning planter class.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] At the beginning of the Civil War, a parole system operated, under which captives agreed not to fight until exchanged.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] They were held in camps run by their army, paid, but not allowed to perform any military duties.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The system of exchanges collapsed in 1863 when the Confederacy refused to exchange black prisoners.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] After that, approximately 56,000 of the 409,000 POWs died in prisons, accounting for 10 percent of the conflict's fatalities.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Leonard writes that between 500 and 1,000 women enlisted as soldiers on both sides, disguised as men.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Women also served as spies, resistance activists, nurses, and hospital personnel.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Women served on the Union hospital ship *Red Rover* and nursed Union and Confederate troops at field hospitals.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Mary Edwards Walker, the only woman ever to receive the Medal of Honor, served in the Union Army and was given the medal for treating the wounded during the war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] One woman, Jennie Hodgers, fought for the Union under the name Albert D.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] After she returned to civilian life, she continued to live as a man until she died in 1915 at the age of 71.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] During the war, women in the North advocated for social reforms and created ladies' aid societies, also called soldiers' aid societies, which provided supplies to soldiers on the battlefield and cared for sick and wounded soldiers.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Women in the North also held military rallies, village parades, and charity bazaars.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Anthony saw that supporting the war effort was a way to pave the future for women's suffrage movements.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] In her appeal to Northern women's loyalty, Anthony challenged the inconsistencies of the nation's founding ideal and its actual practices concerning equality among women.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Northern women during the Civil War also made great strides in the workforce, as they helped contribute to the war effort by stepping into roles that were traditionally held by men.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] While women rarely worked in factories before the war, many filled men's places as they felt they could erase some of the boundaries that separated them from male preserves of power.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Women were important in the workforce as they prepared and packed provisions, sewed uniforms and havelocks, and knitted socks and mittens.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] By entering these new environments, women made significant progress in the fight for women's equality in the workforce.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Northern women were also essential in the wartime support, as they were active participants in the war narrative.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] While women were not allowed to fight on the battlefield in the Civil War, they exhibited a patriotism that gave them the strength to maintain courage for themselves as well as their households.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] While their men were off at war, Northern women created a landscape that emphasized love, sacrifice, and the nurturing of men's courage.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] This is demonstrated in feminized war literature that encouraged, expressed, and valorized men's patriotism.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Women's unwavering encouragement and affection towards fighting men became a cornerstone of the war effort as it helped sustain the spirits of the men on the frontlines.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Confederate women during the Civil War focused on preserving the central economic institution of the Old South: the plantation.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] With so many men away at war, women were left with the land and the slaves.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] While some women hired male overseers to assist them in directing and maintaining newly female-headed plantations, other women decided to stay at the plantations and run the plantations themselves.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Southern women became focused on keeping the economic structure of the South as they dealt with increasingly rebellious slaves.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The South relied on enslaved labor because it was an agrarian economy.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] A good number of enslaved men labored for the Confederate army during the war, which meant that enslaved women and children were increasingly at the center of the work force on the plantations.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] White Southern women struggled to maintain morale on the home front as they dealt with problems without men.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Although Southern women were devoted to the Confederacy, many requested that their sons and husbands be discharged from the military to help them at home.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Eliza Adams wrote to the Confederate government to appeal for exemptions for her sons' military service, as she had sent five sons and also sons-in-laws to fight for the Confederacy.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Southern women were torn between their patriotic ideals and their daily realities of life on the home front.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The Union navy in 1861 was relatively small but, by 1865, expanded rapidly to 6,000 officers, 45,000 sailors, and 671 vessels totaling 510,396 tons.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Its mission was to blockade Confederate ports, control the river system, defend against Confederate raiders on the high seas, and be ready for a possible war with the British Royal Navy.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The main riverine war was fought in the West, where major rivers gave access to the Confederate heartland.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The US Navy eventually controlled the Red, Tennessee, Cumberland, Mississippi, and Ohio rivers.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] In the East, the Navy shelled Confederate forts and supported coastal army operations.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The Civil War occurred during the early stages of the industrial revolution, leading to naval innovations, including the ironclad warship.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy, recognizing the need to counter the Union's naval superiority, built or converted over 130 vessels, including 26 ironclads.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Despite these efforts, Confederate ships were largely unsuccessful against Union ironclads.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The Union navy used timberclads, tinclads, and armored gunboats.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy experimented with the submarine CSS *Hunley*, which proved unsuccessful, and with the ironclad CSS *Virginia*, rebuilt from the sunken Union ship *Merrimack*.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] On March 8, 1862, *Virginia* inflicted significant damage on the Union's wooden fleet, but the next day, the first Union ironclad, USS *Monitor*, arrived to challenge it in the Chesapeake Bay.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The resulting three-hour Battle of Hampton Roads was a draw, proving ironclads were effective warships.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy scuttled the *Virginia* to prevent its capture, while the Union built many copies of the *Monitor*.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy's efforts to obtain warships from Great Britain failed, as Britain had no interest in selling warships to a nation at war with a stronger enemy and feared souring relations with the US.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] By early 1861, General Winfield Scott had devised the Anaconda Plan to win the war with minimal bloodshed, calling for a blockade of the Confederacy to suffocate the South into surrender.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln adopted parts of the plan but opted for a more active war strategy.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] In April 1861, Lincoln announced a blockade of all Southern ports; commercial ships could not get insurance, ending regular traffic.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The South blundered by embargoing cotton exports before the blockade was fully effective; by the time they reversed this decision, it was too late.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] "King Cotton" was dead, as the South could export less than 10% of its cotton.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The blockade shut down the ten Confederate seaports with railheads that moved almost all the cotton.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] By June 1861, warships were stationed off the principal Southern ports, and a year later nearly 300 ships were in service.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederates began the war short on military supplies, which the agrarian South could not produce in adequate numbers.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Northern arms manufacturers were restricted by an embargo, ending existing and future contracts with the South.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy turned to foreign sources, connecting with financiers and companies like S.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Isaac, Campbell & Company and the London Armoury Company in Britain, becoming the Confederacy's main source of arms.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] To transport arms safely to the Confederacy, British investors built small, fast, steam-driven blockade runners that traded arms and supplies from Britain, through Bermuda, Cuba, and the Bahamas in exchange for high-priced cotton.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Many were lightweight and designed for speed, only carrying small amounts of cotton back to England.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] When the Union Navy seized a blockade runner, the ship and cargo were condemned as a prize of war and sold, with proceeds given to the Navy sailors; the captured crewmen, mostly British, were released.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The Southern economy nearly collapsed during the war due to multiple factors, the most notable being severe food shortages, failing railroads, loss of control over key rivers, foraging by Northern armies, and the seizure of animals and crops by Confederate forces.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Historians agree the blockade was a major factor in ruining the Confederate economy; however, Wise argues blockade runners provided enough of a lifeline to allow Robert E.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Lee, a Confederate general, to continue fighting for additional months, as a result of supplies that included 400,000 rifles, lead, blankets, and boots that the Confederate economy could no longer supply.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederate cotton crop became nearly useless, which cut off the Confederacy's primary income source.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Critical imports were scarce, and coastal trade also largely ended.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The blockade's success was not measured by the few ships, which slipped through, but by the thousands that never tried.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] European merchant ships could not obtain insurance for their ships and transport, and were too slow to evade the blockade, leading them to cease docking in Confederate ports.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] To fight an offensive war, the Confederacy purchased arms in Britain and converted British-built ships into commerce raiders, which targeted United States Merchant Marine ships in the Atlantic and Pacific oceans.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy smuggled 600,000 arms, enabling it to continue fighting for two more years.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] As insurance rates soared, American-flagged ships largely ceased traveling in international waters, though some were reflagged with European flags, which allowed them to continue operating.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] After the conclusion of the Civil War, the US government demanded Britain reimburse it for the damage caused by blockade runners and raiders outfitted in British ports.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Britain paid the US$15 million in 1871, which covered costs associated with commerce raiding but nothing more.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Although the Confederacy hoped Britain and France would join them against the Union, this was never likely, so they sought to bring them in as mediators.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The Union worked to block this and threatened war against any country that recognized the Confederacy.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] In 1861, Southerners voluntarily embargoed cotton shipments, hoping to start an economic depression in Europe that would force Britain to enter the war, but this failed.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Worse, Europe turned to Egypt and India for cotton, which they found superior, hindering the South's postwar recovery.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Cotton diplomacy proved a failure, because Europe had a surplus of cotton, while the 1860–62 crop failures in Europe made the North's grain exports critically important.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] It also helped turn European opinion against the Confederacy.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] It was said that "King Corn was more powerful than King Cotton", as US grain increased from a quarter to almost half of British imports.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Meanwhile, the war created jobs for arms makers, ironworkers, and ships to transport weapons.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Lincoln's administration initially struggled to appeal to European public opinion.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] At first, diplomats explained that the US was not committed to ending slavery and emphasized legal arguments about the unconstitutionality of secession.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Confederate representatives, however, focused on their struggle for liberty, commitment to free trade, and the essential role of cotton in the European economy.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The European aristocracy was "absolutely gleeful in pronouncing the American debacle as proof that the entire experiment in popular government had failed.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] European government leaders welcomed the fragmentation of the ascendant American Republic." However, a European public with liberal sensibilities remained, which the US sought to appeal to by building connections with the international press.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] By 1861, Union diplomats like Carl Schurz realized emphasizing the war against slavery was the Union's most effective moral asset in swaying European public opinion.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Seward was concerned an overly radical case for reunification would distress European merchants with cotton interests; even so, he supported a widespread campaign of public diplomacy.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] US minister to Britain Charles Francis Adams proved adept and convinced Britain not to challenge the Union blockade.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The Confederacy purchased warships from commercial shipbuilders in Britain, with the most famous being the CSS *Alabama*, which caused considerable damage and led to serious postwar disputes.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] However, public opinion against slavery in Britain created a political liability for politicians, where the anti-slavery movement was powerful.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] War loomed in late 1861 between the US and Britain over the *Trent* Affair, which began when US Navy personnel boarded the British ship *Trent* and seized two Confederate diplomats.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] However, London and Washington smoothed this over after Lincoln released the two men.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Prince Albert left his deathbed to issue diplomatic instructions to Lord Lyons during the *Trent* Affair.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] His request was honored, and, as a result, the British response to the US was toned down, helping avert war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] In 1862, the British government considered mediating between the Union and Confederacy, though such an offer would have risked war with the US.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] British prime minister Lord Palmerston reportedly read *Uncle Tom's Cabin* three times when deciding what his decision would be.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The Union victory at the Battle of Antietam caused the British to delay this decision.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] The Emancipation Proclamation increased the political liability of supporting the Confederacy.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Realizing that Washington could not intervene in Mexico as long as the Confederacy controlled Texas, France invaded Mexico in 1861 and installed the Habsburg Austrian archduke Maximilian I as emperor.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Washington repeatedly protested France's violation of the Monroe Doctrine.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Despite sympathy for the Confederacy, France's seizure of Mexico deterred it from war with the Union.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Confederate offers late in the war to end slavery in return for diplomatic recognition were not seriously considered by London or Paris.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] After 1863, the Polish revolt against Russia further distracted the European powers and ensured they remained neutral.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] Russia supported the Union, largely because it believed the US counterbalanced its geopolitical rival, the UK.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p01] In 1863, the Imperial Russian Navy's Baltic and Pacific fleets wintered in the American ports of New York and San Francisco, respectively.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The Eastern theater refers to the military operations east of the Appalachian Mountains, including Virginia, West Virginia, Maryland, and Pennsylvania, the District of Columbia, and the coastal fortifications and seaports of North Carolina.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan took command of the Union Army of the Potomac on July 26, 1861, and the war began in earnest in 1862.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Ohio forces would advance through Kentucky into Tennessee.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The Missouri Department would drive south along the Mississippi River.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The westernmost attack would originate from Kansas.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The primary Confederate force in the Eastern theater was the Army of Northern Virginia.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The Army originated as the (Confederate) Army of the Potomac, which was organized on June 20, 1861, from all operational forces in Northern Virginia.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] On July 20 and 21, the Army of the Shenandoah and forces from the District of Harpers Ferry were added.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Units from the Army of the Northwest were merged into the Army of the Potomac between March 14 and May 17, 1862.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The Army of the Potomac was renamed *Army of Northern Virginia* on March 14.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The Army of the Peninsula was merged into it on April 12, 1862.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] When Virginia declared its secession in April 1861, Robert E.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Lee chose to follow his home state, despite his desire for the country to remain intact and an offer of a senior Union command.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] In his four-volume biography of Lee published in 1934 and 1935, historian Douglas S.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Freeman wrote that the army received its final name from Lee when he issued orders assuming command on June 1, 1862.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] However, Freeman wrote, Lee corresponded with Brigadier General Joseph E.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Johnston, his predecessor in army command, before that date and referred to Johnston's command as the Army of Northern Virginia.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Part of the confusion results from the fact that Johnston commanded the Department of Northern Virginia as of October 22, 1861, and the name Army of Northern Virginia was seen as an informal consequence of its parent department's name.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Jefferson Davis and Johnston did not adopt the name, but the organization of units as of March 14 was clearly the same organization that Lee received on June 1, and is generally referred to as the Army of Northern Virginia, even if that is correct only in retrospect.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] On July 4 at Harper's Ferry, Colonel Thomas J.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Jackson assigned Jeb Stuart command of all cavalry companies of the Army of the Shenandoah, and Jackson eventually commanded the Army of Northern Virginia's cavalry.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Called the "Philippi Races" because of its brevity, Philippi, Virginia (now Philippi, WV) was the scene of the first organized land action of the American Civil War, on June 3, 1861.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] In July 1861, in the first in a series of prominent battles in the war, Union Army troops commanded by Maj.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Irvin McDowell attacked Confederate forces, which were under the command of Beauregard near the national capital in Washington.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederacy repelled the attack in the First Battle of Bull Run.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] At the beginning of the battle, the Union appeared to hold the upper hand.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The Union Army routed Confederate forces, then holding defensive positions, but Confederate reinforcements under Joseph E.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Johnston arrived from the Shenandoah Valley by railroad, and the battle's course quickly changed.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] A brigade of Virginians, commanded by Thomas J.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Jackson, then a relatively unknown brigadier general from Virginia Military Institute, stood its ground, leading to Jackson earning the nickname "Stonewall".
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln urged the Union Army to commence offensive operations against Confederate forces, which led General George B.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan, in the spring of 1862, to attack Virginia by way of the peninsula between the York River and James River southeast of Richmond.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan's army reached the gates of Richmond in the Peninsula campaign.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Also in the spring of 1862, in Shenandoah Valley, Jackson led his Valley Campaign, during which he employed rapid and unpredictable movements on interior lines.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Jackson's 17,000 troops marched 646 miles (1,040 km) in 48 days, during which they won minor battles as they engaged three Union armies, comprising 52,000 men, including those of Nathaniel P.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Frémont, preventing them from reinforcing the Union offensive against Richmond.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The swiftness of Jackson's troops earned them the nickname foot cavalry.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Johnston halted McClellan's advance at the Battle of Seven Pines, but he was wounded in the battle, and Robert E.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Lee and his senior subordinates, James Longstreet and Stonewall Jackson, defeated McClellan in the Seven Days Battles, forcing McClellan's retreat.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] During the Northern Virginia Campaign, which included the Second Battle of Bull Run, Confederate forces registered another important military victory.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan resisted General-in-Chief Halleck's orders to send reinforcements to John Pope's Union Army of Virginia, which enabled Lee's Confederate forces to defeat twice the number of combined enemy troops.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Emboldened by Second Bull Run, Confederate forces launched their first invasion of the North in the Maryland Campaign during which Lee led 45,000 Army of Northern Virginia troops across the Potomac River into Maryland on September 5.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln then restored Pope's troops to McClellan, and McClellan and Lee clashed in the Battle of Antietam near Sharpsburg, Maryland, on September 17, 1862, which proved the bloodiest single day in both the Civil War and US military history.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] McClellan failed to respond in any measurable way to Lee's attempt to invade the North at Antietam, leading to his replacement by Maj.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Burnside led Union Army troops in the Battle of Fredericksburg, where they were defeated on December 13, 1862.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Over 12,000 Union soldiers were killed or wounded during futile attempts by Union troops to launch frontal assaults against Marye's Heights.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] After the battle, Burnside was replaced by Maj.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Hooker, too, proved unable to defeat Lee's army; despite having more than twice as many troops as Lee, Hooker's Chancellorsville Campaign proved ineffective, and he was soundly defeated in the Battle of Chancellorsville, which was fought between April 30 and May 6, 1863.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Chancellorsville is known as Lee's "perfect battle" because his risky decision to divide his army paid off.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] During the Battle of Chancellorsville, Stonewall Jackson was shot in his left arm and right hand by friendly fire, leading to the amputation of his arm, and he died of pneumonia.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The fiercest fighting of the battle—and the second bloodiest day of the Civil War—occurred on May 3 as Lee launched multiple attacks against the Union position at Chancellorsville.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] That same day, John Sedgwick advanced across the Rappahannock River, defeated the small Confederate force at Marye's Heights in the Second Battle of Fredericksburg, and then moved westward, but Confederate forces succeeded in delaying Union forces in the Battle of Salem Church.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] George Meade during Lee's second invasion of the North, in June.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] In the Battle of Gettysburg, which proved the war's bloodiest and one of its most strategically significant, Meade defeated Lee in a three-day battle between July 1 and 3, 1863.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The Battle of Gettysburg caused over 50,000 Union and Confederate casualties, but also proved the war's turning point, altering the course of the war in the Union's favor.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Pickett's Charge, launched July 3, on the final day of the Battle of Gettysburg, is considered the high-water mark of the Confederacy, representing the collapse of any credible prospect that the Confederacy could prevail in the war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] At Gettysburg, Lee's Army of Northern Virginia suffered 28,000 casualties versus Meade's 23,000, and Lee was repelled in a failed attempt to invade and occupy Union territory.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The Western theater refers to military operations between the Appalachian Mountains and the Mississippi River, including Alabama, Georgia, Florida, Mississippi, North Carolina, Kentucky, South Carolina, Tennessee, and parts of Louisiana.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The primary Union forces in this theater were the Army of the Tennessee and Army of the Cumberland, named for the two rivers, Tennessee River and Cumberland River.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] After Meade's inconclusive fall campaign, Lincoln turned to the Western theater for new leadership.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] At the same time, the Confederate stronghold of Vicksburg surrendered, giving the Union control of the Mississippi River, permanently isolating the western Confederacy, and producing the new leader Lincoln needed, Ulysses S.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The Army of Tennessee, which served as the primary Confederate force in the Western theater, was formed on November 20, 1862, when General Braxton Bragg renamed the former Army of Mississippi.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] While Confederate forces had successes in the Eastern theater, they were defeated many times in the West.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The Union's key strategist and tactician in the West was Ulysses S.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Grant, who led the Union to victories in battles at Fort Henry (February 6, 1862) and Fort Donelson (February 11 to 16, 1862), earning him the nickname of "Unconditional Surrender" Grant.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] With these victories, the Union gained control of the Tennessee and Cumberland Rivers.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Nathan Bedford Forrest rallied nearly 4,000 Confederate troops and led them to escape across the Cumberland River.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Nashville and central Tennessee fell to the Union, leading to attrition of local food supplies and livestock and a breakdown in social organization.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate general Leonidas Polk subsequently invaded Columbus, Kentucky, which ended Kentucky's policy of neutrality and turned it against the Confederacy.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Grant used river transport and Andrew Hull Foote's gunboats of the Western Flotilla, threatening the Confederacy's "Gibraltar of the West" in Columbus, Kentucky.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Although rebuffed at Belmont, Grant cut off Columbus.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate forces, lacking their gunboats, were forced to retreat and the Union took control of west Kentucky and opened Tennessee in March 1862.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] At the Battle of Shiloh, in Shiloh, Tennessee, in April 1862, Confederate forces launched a surprise attack on Union forces, pushing them back to the Tennessee River as night fell.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Over that night, however, the Navy landed reinforcements, and Grant counterattacked.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Grant and the Union ultimately won a decisive victory in the first battle with a high number of casualties in what proved to be the first in a series of such battles.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate forces lost Albert Sidney Johnston, considered their finest general, before Lee emerged to assume command.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] One of the early Union objectives was to capture the Mississippi River, which would permit it to cut the Confederacy in half.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The Mississippi was opened to Union traffic to the southern border of Tennessee after it took Island No.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] 10, New Madrid, Missouri, and then Memphis, Tennessee.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] In April 1862, the Union Navy captured New Orleans.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] "The key to the river was New Orleans, the South's largest port [and] greatest industrial center." US naval forces under Farragut ran past Confederate defenses south of New Orleans.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate forces abandoned the city, giving the Union a critical anchor in the deep South, which allowed Union forces to move up the Mississippi.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Memphis fell to Union forces on June 6, 1862, allowing it to serve as a key base for further Union advances south along the Mississippi.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] On the Mississippi River, the Union took every fortress city with the exception of Vicksburg, Mississippi.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] But Confederate control of Vicksburg was sufficient in preventing the Union from controlling the entire river.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Bragg's second invasion of Kentucky in the Confederate Heartland Offensive included initial successes, including Kirby Smith's triumph in the Battle of Richmond and the capture of the Kentucky capital of Frankfort, Kentucky, on September 3, 1862.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The campaign ended with a meaningless victory over Maj.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Don Carlos Buell at the Battle of Perryville, and Bragg was forced to end his attempt to invade and control Kentucky.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Lacking logistical support and infantry recruits, Bragg was instead forced to retreat, and ended up being narrowly defeated by Maj.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] William Rosecrans in the Battle of Stones River in Tennessee in what proved to be the culmination of the Stones River Campaign.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] US naval forces assisted Grant in the long, complex Vicksburg Campaign, which resulted in Confederate forces surrendering in the Battle of Vicksburg in July 1863, which cemented Union control of the Mississippi River in one of the war's turning points.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The one clear Confederate victory in the West was the Battle of Chickamauga.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] After Rosecrans' successful Tullahoma Campaign, Bragg, reinforced by Lt.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] James Longstreet's Corps, defeated Rosecrans, despite the defensive stand of Maj.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Rosecrans retreated to Chattanooga, Tennessee, where Bragg was then besieged in the Chattanooga campaign.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Grant marched to the relief of Rosecrans, where he led the defeat of Bragg in the Third Battle of Chattanooga, eventually causing Longstreet to abandon his Knoxville Campaign and driving Confederate forces out of Tennessee and opening a route to Atlanta and the heart of the Confederacy.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The Trans-Mississippi theater refers to military operations west of the Mississippi, encompassing most of Missouri, Arkansas, most of Louisiana, and the Indian Territory in present-day Oklahoma.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The Union's command was the Trans-Mississippi Division, or the Military Division of West Mississippi.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The first major battle of the Trans-Mississippi theater was the Battle of Wilson's Creek (August 1861).
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederates were driven from Missouri early in the war as a result of the Battle of Pea Ridge.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Extensive guerrilla warfare characterized the trans-Mississippi region, as the Confederacy lacked the troops and logistics to support regular armies that could challenge Union control.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Roving Confederate bands such as Quantrill's Raiders terrorized the countryside, striking military installations and civilian settlements.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The "Sons of Liberty" and "Order of the American Knights" attacked pro-Union people, elected officeholders, and unarmed uniformed soldiers.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] These partisans could not be driven out of Missouri, until an entire regular Union infantry division was engaged.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] By 1864, these violent activities harmed the nationwide antiwar movement organizing against the re-election of Lincoln.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Missouri not only stayed in the Union, but Lincoln took 70 percent of the vote to win re-election.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Small-scale military actions south and west of Missouri sought to control Indian Territory and New Mexico Territory for the Union.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The Battle of Glorieta Pass was the decisive battle of the New Mexico Campaign.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The Union repulsed Confederate incursions into New Mexico in 1862, and the exiled Arizona government withdrew into Texas.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] In the Indian Territory, civil war broke out within tribes.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] About 12,000 Indian warriors fought for the Confederacy but fewer for the Union.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The most prominent Cherokee was Brigadier General Stand Watie, the last Confederate general to surrender.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] After the fall of Vicksburg in July 1863, Jefferson Davis informed General Kirby Smith in Texas that he could expect no further help from east of the Mississippi.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Although he lacked resources to beat Union armies, he built up a formidable arsenal at Tyler, along with his own Kirby Smithdom economy, a virtual "independent fiefdom" in Texas, including railroad construction and international smuggling.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The Union, in turn, did not directly engage him.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The Union's 1864 Red River Campaign to take Shreveport, Louisiana, failed and Texas remained in Confederate hands throughout the war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The lower seaboard theater refers to military and naval operations that occurred near the coastal areas of the Southeast as well as the southern part of the Mississippi.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Union naval activities were dictated by the Anaconda Plan.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] One of the earliest battles was fought in November 1861 at Port Royal Sound, south of Charleston.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Much of the war along the South Carolina coast concentrated on capturing Charleston.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] In attempting to capture Charleston, the Union military tried two approaches: by land over James or Morris Islands or through the harbor.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] However, the Confederates were able to drive back each attack.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] A famous land attack was the Second Battle of Fort Wagner, in which the 54th Massachusetts Infantry took part.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The Union suffered a serious defeat, losing 1,515 soldiers while the Confederates lost only 174.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] However, the 54th was hailed for its valor, which encouraged the general acceptance of the recruitment of African American soldiers into the Union Army, which reinforced the Union's numerical advantage.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Fort Pulaski on the Georgia coast was an early target for the Union navy.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Following the capture of Port Royal, an expedition was organized with engineer troops under the command of Captain Quincy Adams Gillmore, forcing a Confederate surrender.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The Union army occupied the fort for the rest of the war after repairing it.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] In April 1862, a Union naval task force commanded by Commander David Dixon Porter attacked Forts Jackson and St.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Philip, which guarded the river approach to New Orleans from the south.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] While part of the fleet bombarded the forts, other vessels forced a break in the obstructions in the river and enabled the rest of the fleet to steam upriver to the city.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Benjamin Butler landed near the forts and forced their surrender.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Butler's controversial command of New Orleans earned him the nickname "Beast".
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The following year, the Union Army of the Gulf commanded by Maj.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Banks laid siege to Port Hudson for nearly eight weeks, the longest siege in US military history.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederates attempted to defend with the Bayou Teche Campaign but surrendered after Vicksburg.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] These surrenders gave the Union control over the Mississippi.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Several skirmishes but no major battles were fought in Florida.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The biggest was the Battle of Olustee in early 1864.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The Pacific coast theater refers to military operations on the Pacific Ocean and in the states and territories west of the Continental Divide.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] At the beginning of 1864, Lincoln made Grant commander of all Union armies.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Grant made his headquarters with the Army of the Potomac and put Maj.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] William Tecumseh Sherman in command of most of the western armies.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Grant understood the concept of total war and believed, along with Lincoln and Sherman, that only the utter defeat of Confederate forces and their economic base would end the war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] This was total war not in killing civilians, but in injuring the Confederacy's capacity to produce and transport the supplies needed to continue the war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Sherman, at Grant's direction, seized provisions and destroyed homes, farms, and railroads, which Grant said "would otherwise have gone to the support of secession and rebellion.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Grant devised a coordinated strategy that would strike at the entire Confederacy from multiple directions.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Generals Meade and Benjamin Butler were ordered to move against Lee near Richmond, General Franz Sigel was to attack the Shenandoah Valley, General Sherman was to capture Atlanta and march to the Atlantic Ocean, Generals George Crook and William W.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Averell were to operate against railroad supply lines in West Virginia, and Maj.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Grant's army set out on the Overland Campaign intending to draw Lee into a defense of Richmond, where they would attempt to pin down and destroy the Confederate army.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The Union army first attempted to maneuver past Lee and fought several battles, notably at the Wilderness, Spotsylvania, and Cold Harbor.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] These resulted in heavy losses on both sides and forced Lee's Confederates to fall back repeatedly.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] At the Battle of Yellow Tavern, the Confederates lost Jeb Stuart.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] An attempt to outflank Lee from the south failed under Butler, who was trapped inside the Bermuda Hundred river bend.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Each battle resulted in setbacks for the Union that mirrored those they had suffered under prior generals, though unlike them, Grant chose to fight on rather than retreat.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Grant was tenacious and kept pressing Lee's Army of Northern Virginia back to Richmond.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] While Lee was preparing for an attack on Richmond, Grant unexpectedly turned south to cross the James River and began the protracted Siege of Petersburg, where the two armies engaged in trench warfare for over nine months.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] To deny the Confederacy continued use of the Shenandoah Valley as a base from which to launch invasions of Maryland and the Washington area, and to threaten Lee's supply lines for his forces, Grant launched the Valley campaigns in May 1864.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Sigel were repelled at the Battle of New Market by Confederate Gen.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The Battle of New Market was the Confederacy's last major victory, and included a charge by teenage VMI cadets.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] After relieving Sigel, and following mixed performances by his successor, Grant finally found a commander, General Philip Sheridan, aggressive enough to prevail against the army of Maj.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] After a cautious start, Sheridan defeated Early in a series of battles in September and October 1864, including a decisive defeat at the Battle of Cedar Creek.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Sheridan then proceeded through that winter to destroy the agricultural base of the Shenandoah Valley, a strategy similar to the tactics Sherman later employed in Georgia.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Meanwhile, Sherman maneuvered from Chattanooga to Atlanta, defeating Confederate Generals Joseph E.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The fall of Atlanta on September 2, 1864, guaranteed the reelection of Lincoln.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Hood left the Atlanta area to swing around and menace Sherman's supply lines and invade Tennessee in the Franklin–Nashville Campaign.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] John Schofield defeated Hood at the Battle of Franklin, and George H.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Thomas dealt Hood a massive defeat at the Battle of Nashville, effectively destroying Hood's army.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Leaving Atlanta, and his base of supplies, Sherman's army marched, with no destination set, laying waste to about 20 percent of the farms in Georgia on his March to the Sea.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] He reached the Atlantic at Savannah, Georgia, in December 1864.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Sherman's army was followed by thousands of freed slaves; there were no major battles along the march.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Sherman turned north through South Carolina and North Carolina in his Carolinas campaign, to approach the Confederate Virginia lines from the south, increasing the pressure on Lee's army.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Lee's army, thinned by desertion and casualties, was now much smaller than Grant's.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] One last Confederate attempt to break the Union hold on Petersburg failed at the decisive Battle of Five Forks on April 1.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The Union now controlled the entire perimeter surrounding Richmond–Petersburg, completely cutting it off from the Confederacy.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Realizing the capital was now lost, Lee's army and the Confederate government were forced to evacuate.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederate capital fell on April 2–3, to the Union XXV Corps, composed of black troops.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The remaining Confederate units fled west after a defeat at Sayler's Creek on April 6.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] front page celebrated Lee's surrender, headlining how Grant let Confederate officers retain their sidearms and "paroled" the Confederate officers and men.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] News of Lee's April 9 surrender reached this southern newspaper (Savannah, Georgia) on April 15—after the April 14 shooting of President Lincoln.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The article quotes Grant's terms of surrender.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Lee did not intend to surrender, but planned to regroup at Appomattox Station, where supplies were to be waiting, and then continue the war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Grant chased Lee and got in front of him, so that when Lee's army reached the village of Appomattox Court House, they were surrounded.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] After an initial battle, Lee decided the fight was hopeless, and surrendered his Army of Northern Virginia to Grant on April 9, 1865, during a conference at the McLean House.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] In an untraditional gesture and as a sign of Grant's respect and anticipation of peacefully restoring Confederate states to the Union, Lee was permitted to keep his sword and horse, Traveller.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] His men were paroled, and a chain of Confederate surrenders began.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] On April 14, 1865, Lincoln was shot by John Wilkes Booth, a Confederate sympathizer.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's vice president, Andrew Johnson, was unharmed, because his would-be assassin, George Atzerodt, lost his nerve, so Johnson was immediately sworn in as president.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Meanwhile, Confederate forces across the South surrendered, as news of Lee's surrender reached them.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] On April 26, the same day Sergeant Boston Corbett killed Booth at a tobacco barn, Johnston surrendered nearly 90,000 troops of the Army of Tennessee to Sherman at Bennett Place, near present-day Durham, North Carolina.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] It proved to be the largest surrender of Confederate forces.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] On May 4, all remaining Confederate forces in Alabama, Mississippi, and Louisiana east of the Mississippi, under the command of Lt.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate president Davis was captured in retreat at Irwinville, Georgia on May 10.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The final land battle was fought on May 13, 1865, at the Battle of Palmito Ranch in Texas.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Buckner, acting for Edmund Smith, signed a military convention surrendering Confederate forces in the Trans-Mississippi Department.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] This date is often cited by contemporaries and historians as the effective end date of the war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] On June 2, with most of his troops having already gone home, a reluctant Kirby Smith had little choice but to sign the official surrender document.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] General Stand Watie became the last Confederate general to surrender his forces.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Gordon Granger announced General Order No.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] 3, bringing the Emancipation Proclamation into effect in Texas and freeing the last slaves of the Confederacy.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The anniversary of this date is now celebrated as Juneteenth.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The naval part of the war ended more slowly.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Britain finally responded on June 6, by transmitting a letter from Foreign Secretary John Russell, 1st Earl Russell, to the Lords of the Admiralty withdrawing rights to Confederate warships to enter British ports and waters.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] US Secretary of State Seward welcomed the withdrawal of concessions to the Confederates.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Finally, on October 18, Russell advised the Admiralty that the time specified in his June message had elapsed and "all measures of a restrictive nature on vessels of war of the United States in British ports, harbors, and waters, are now to be considered as at an end".
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Nonetheless, the final Confederate surrender was in Liverpool, England where James Iredell Waddell, the captain of CSS *Shenandoah*, surrendered the cruiser to British authorities on November 6.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Legally, the war did not end until August 20, 1866, when President Johnson issued a proclamation that declared "that the said insurrection is at an end and that peace, order, tranquillity, and civil authority now exist in and throughout the whole of the United States of America".
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The causes of the war, reasons for its outcome, and even its name are subjects of lingering contention.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The North and West grew wealthy while the once-rich South became poor for a century.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The national political power of the slaveowners and rich Southerners ended.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Historians are less sure about the results of postwar Reconstruction, especially regarding the second-class citizenship of the freedmen and their poverty.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Historians have debated whether the Confederacy could have won the war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] McPherson, argue Confederate victory was possible.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] McPherson argues that the North's advantage in population and resources made Northern victory likely, but not guaranteed.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] He argues that if the Confederacy had fought using unconventional tactics, it would have more easily been able to hold out long enough to exhaust the Union.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Confederates did not need to invade and hold enemy territory to win, but only to fight a defensive war to convince the North the cost of winning was too high.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The North needed to conquer and hold vast stretches of enemy territory and defeat Confederate armies to win.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln was not a military dictator and could fight only as long as the American public supported the war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederacy sought to win independence by outlasting Lincoln; however, after Atlanta fell and Lincoln defeated McClellan in the election of 1864, hope for a political victory for the South ended.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln had secured the support of the Republicans, War Democrats, border states, emancipated slaves, and the neutrality of Britain and France.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] By defeating the Democrats and McClellan, he defeated the Copperheads, who had wanted a negotiated peace with the Confederacy.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Some scholars argue the Union held an insurmountable long-term advantage over the Confederacy in industrial strength and population.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Confederate actions, they argue, only delayed defeat.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] A minority view among historians is that the Confederacy lost because, as E.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Merton Coulter put it, "people did not will hard enough and long enough to win".
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] However, most historians reject the argument.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] McPherson, after reading thousands of letters written by Confederate soldiers, found strong patriotism that continued to the end; they truly believed they were fighting for freedom and liberty.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Even as the Confederacy was visibly collapsing in 1864–65, most Confederate soldiers were fighting hard.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Also important were Lincoln's eloquence in articulating the national purpose and his skill in keeping the border states committed to the Union cause.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The Emancipation Proclamation was an effective use of the president's war powers.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The Confederate government failed to get Europe involved militarily.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Southern leaders needed to get European powers to help break the blockade the Union had created around Southern ports.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's naval blockade was 95 percent effective at stopping trade goods; as a result, imports and exports to the South declined significantly.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The abundance of European cotton and Britain's hostility to slavery, along with Lincoln's naval blockades, severely decreased any chance that Britain or France would enter the war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Doyle has argued that the Union victory had a major impact on world history.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The Union victory energized popular democratic forces.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] A Confederate victory, on the other hand, would have meant a new birth of slavery, not of freedom.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Scholars have debated what the effects of the war were on political and economic power in the South.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The prevailing view is that the southern planter elite retained its powerful position in the South.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] However, a 2017 study challenges this, noting that while some Southern elites retained their economic status, the turmoil of the 1860s created greater opportunities for economic mobility in the South, than in the North.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Exact casualty figures were collected for the Union, but Confederate records were poorly kept, or lost in the chaos of defeat.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Thus, the casualty figures are imprecise and based on statistical extrapolation.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Neither side kept a tally of civilian deaths due to the war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] In the 19th century, the death toll had been estimated at a lower 620,000.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] In 2011, the death toll was recalculated based on a 1% sample of census data, yielding approximately 750,000 soldier deaths, 20 percent higher than traditionally estimated, and possibly as high as 850,000.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The figure was recalculated to 698,000 soldier deaths in 2024 after examining newly available full census records.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Mortality rates among men were as high as 19 percent in Louisiana, and 16.6–16.7 percent in Georgia and South Carolina respectively.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The war resulted in at least 1,030,000 casualties (3 percent of the population), including an estimated 698,000 soldier deaths—two-thirds by disease.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Based on 1860 census figures, 8 percent of all white men aged 13–43 died in the war, including 6 percent in the North and 18 percent in the South.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] About 56,000 soldiers died in prison camps during the War.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] An estimated 60,000 soldiers lost limbs.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] As McPherson notes, the war's "cost in American lives was as great as in all of the nation's other wars combined through Vietnam".
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] In addition, there were 4,523 deaths in the Navy (2,112 in battle) and 460 in the Marines (148 in battle).
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The US Colored Troops made up 10 percent of the Union death toll—15 percent of Union deaths from disease and less than 3 percent of those killed in battle.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Losses among African Americans were high.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] In the last year and a half and from all reported casualties, approximately 20 percent of all African Americans enrolled in the military died during the war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Their mortality rate was significantly higher than white soldiers.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] While 15 percent of US Volunteers and just 9 percent of white Regular Army troops died, 21 percent of US Colored Troops died.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] While the figures of 360,000 army deaths for the Union and 260,000 for the Confederacy remained commonly cited, they are incomplete.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] This often happened only days or weeks later.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Francis Amasa Walker, superintendent of the 1870 census, used census and surgeon general data to estimate a minimum of 500,000 Union military deaths and 350,000 Confederate military deaths, a total of 850,000 soldiers.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] While Walker's estimates were originally dismissed because of the 1870 census's undercounting, it was later found that the census was only off by 6.5 percent and that the data Walker used would be roughly accurate.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Losses were far higher than during the war with Mexico, which saw roughly 13,000 American deaths, including fewer than two thousand killed in battle, between 1846 and 1848.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] One reason for the high number of battle deaths in the civil war was the continued use of tactics similar to those of the Napoleonic Wars, such as charging.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] With the advent of more accurate rifled barrels, Minié balls, and (near the end of the war for the Union) repeating firearms such as the Spencer repeating rifle and the Henry repeating rifle, soldiers were mowed down when standing in lines in the open.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] This led to the adoption of trench warfare, a style of fighting that defined much of World War I.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Deaths among former slaves has proven hard to estimate, due to the lack of reliable census data, though they were known to be considerable, as former slaves were set free or escaped in massive numbers in areas where the Union army did not have sufficient shelter, doctors, or food for them.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Professor Jim Downs states that tens of thousands to hundreds of thousands of slaves died during the war from disease, starvation, or exposure, and that if these deaths are counted in the war's total, the death toll would exceed 1 million.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] It is estimated that during the war, of the equines killed, including horses, mules, donkeys and even confiscated children's ponies, over 32,600 of them belonged to the Union and 45,800 the Confederacy.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] However, other estimates place the total at 1,000,000.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] It is estimated that 544 Confederate flags were captured during the war by the Union.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The flags were sent to the War Department in Washington.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The Union flags captured by the Confederates were sent to Richmond.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Abolishing slavery was not a Union war goal from the outset but quickly became one.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln initially claimed that preserving the Union was the central goal.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] In contrast, the South fought to preserve slavery.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] While not all Southerners saw themselves as fighting for slavery, most officers and over a third of the rank and file in Lee's army had close family ties to slavery.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] To Northerners, the motivation was primarily to preserve the Union, not to abolish slavery.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's decision to issue the Proclamation angered Peace Democrats ("Copperheads") and War Democrats, but energized most Republicans.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] By warning that free blacks would flood the North, Democrats made gains in the 1862 elections, but they did not gain control of Congress.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The Republicans' counterargument that slavery was the mainstay of the enemy steadily gained support, with the Democrats losing decisively in the 1863 elections in the Northern state of Ohio, when they tried to resurrect anti-black sentiment.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The Emancipation Proclamation legally freed the slaves in states "in rebellion", but, as a practical matter, slavery for the 3.5 million black people in the South effectively ended in each area when Union armies arrived.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The last Confederate slaves were freed on June 19, 1865, celebrated as the modern holiday of Juneteenth.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Slaves in the border states and those in some former Confederate territory occupied before the Emancipation Proclamation were freed by state action or (on December 6, 1865) by the Thirteenth Amendment.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The Emancipation Proclamation enabled African Americans, both free blacks and escaped slaves, to join the Union Army.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] About 190,000 volunteered, further enhancing the numerical advantage the Union armies enjoyed over the Confederates, who did not dare emulate the equivalent manpower source for fear of undermining the legitimacy of slavery.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] During the war, sentiment concerning slaves, enslavement, and emancipation in the United States was divided.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's fears of making slavery a war issue were based on a harsh reality: abolition did not enjoy wide support in the west, the territories, and the border states.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] In 1861, Lincoln worried that premature attempts at emancipation would mean the loss of the border states, and that "to lose Kentucky is nearly the same as to lose the whole game".
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Copperheads and some War Democrats opposed emancipation, although the latter eventually accepted it as part of the total war needed to save the Union.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln reversed attempts at emancipation by Secretary of War Simon Cameron and Generals John C.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Frémont and David Hunter, in an effort to retain the loyalty of the border states and the War Democrats.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln warned the border states that a more radical type of emancipation would happen if they rejected his plan of gradual compensated emancipation and voluntary colonization.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] But compensated emancipation occurred only in the District of Columbia, where Congress had the power to enact it.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] When Lincoln told his cabinet about his proposed emancipation proclamation, which would apply to the states still in rebellion on January 1, 1863, Seward advised Lincoln to wait for a Union military victory before issuing it, because to do otherwise would seem like "our last shriek on the retreat".
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Walter Stahr, however, writes, "There are contemporary sources, however, that suggest others were involved in the decision to delay", and Stahr quotes them.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] , who were fugitive slaves, including cooks, laundresses, laborers, teamsters, railroad repair crews, fled to the Union Army, but were not legally freed until the Emancipation Proclamation, which Lincoln signed on January 1, 1863, more than two years before the end of the Civil War.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] ; seen here are black and white teenaged soldiers who volunteered to fight for the Union.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln laid the groundwork for public support in an open letter published in response to Horace Greeley's "The Prayer of Twenty Millions"; the letter stated that Lincoln's goal was to save the Union, and that, if he freed the slaves, it would be as a means to that end.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] He also had a meeting at the White House with five African American representatives on August 14, 1862.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Arranging for a reporter to be present, he urged his visitors to agree to the voluntary colonization of black people.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's motive for both his letter to Greeley and his statement to the black visitors was apparently to make his forthcoming Emancipation Proclamation more palatable to racist white people.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] A Union victory in the Battle of Antietam on September 17, 1862, provided Lincoln with an opportunity to issue the preliminary Emancipation Proclamation, and the War Governors' Conference added support for the proclamation.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln issued his preliminary Emancipation Proclamation on September 22, 1862.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] It stated that slaves in all states in rebellion on January 1, 1863, would be free.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] He issued his final Emancipation Proclamation on January 1, 1863, keeping his promise.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Hodges, Lincoln explained his belief that "If slavery is not wrong, nothing is wrong....
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] And yet I have never understood that the Presidency conferred upon me an unrestricted right to act officially upon this judgment and feeling....
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Lincoln's moderate approach succeeded in inducing the border states to remain in the Union and War Democrats to support the Union.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The border states, which included Kentucky, Missouri, Maryland, Delaware, and Union-controlled regions around New Orleans, Norfolk, Virginia, and elsewhere, were not covered by the Emancipation Proclamation.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Nor was Tennessee, which had come under Union control.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Missouri and Maryland abolished slavery on their own; Kentucky and Delaware did not.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Still, the proclamation did not enjoy universal support.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] It caused much unrest in what were then considered western states, where racist sentiments led to a great fear of abolition.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] There was some concern that the proclamation would lead to the secession of western states, and its issuance prompted the stationing of Union troops in Illinois in case of rebellion.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] Since the Emancipation Proclamation was based on the president's war powers, it applied only in territory held by Confederates at the time it was issued.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] However, the Proclamation became a symbol of the Union's growing commitment to add emancipation to the Union's definition of liberty.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] The Emancipation Proclamation greatly reduced the Confederacy's hope of being recognized or otherwise aided by Britain or France.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p02] By late 1864, Lincoln was playing a leading role in getting the House of Representatives to vote for the Thirteenth Amendment, which mandated the ending of chattel slavery.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] The war devastated the South and posed serious questions of how it would be reintegrated into the Union.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] The war destroyed much of the South's wealth, in part because wealth held in enslaved people (at least $1,000 each for a healthy adult prior to the war) was wiped off the books.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] All accumulated investment in Confederate bonds was forfeited; most banks and railroads were bankrupt.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] The income per person dropped to less than 40 percent of that of the North, and that lasted into the 20th century.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] Southern influence in the federal government, previously considerable, was greatly diminished until the second half of the 20th century.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] Reconstruction began during the war, with the Emancipation Proclamation of January 1863, and it continued until 1877.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] From the Union perspective, the goals of Reconstruction were to consolidate victory by reuniting the Union, to guarantee a "republican form of government" for the ex-Confederate states, and to permanently end slavery—and prevent semi-slavery status.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] President Johnson, who took office in April 1865, took a lenient approach and saw the achievement of the main war goals as realized in 1865, when each ex-rebel state repudiated secession and ratified the Thirteenth Amendment.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] Radical Republicans demanded proof that Confederate nationalism was dead and that the slaves were truly free.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] They overrode Johnson's vetoes of civil rights legislation, and the House impeached him, although the Senate did not convict him.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] In 1868 and 1872, the Republican candidate Grant won the presidency.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] In 1872, the "Liberal Republicans" argued that the war goals had been achieved and Reconstruction should end.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] They chose Horace Greeley to head a presidential ticket in 1872 but were decisively defeated.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] In 1874, Democrats, primarily Southern, took control of Congress and opposed further reconstruction.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] The Compromise of 1877 closed with a national consensus, except on the part of former slaves, that the war had finally ended.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] With the withdrawal of federal troops, however, white men retook control of every Southern legislature, and the Jim Crow era of disenfranchisement and legal segregation was ushered in.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] The war had a demonstrable impact on American politics.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] Many veterans on both sides were elected to political office, including five US presidents: Ulysses Grant, Rutherford B.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] Garfield, Benjamin Harrison, and William McKinley.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] The war is a central event in American collective memory.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] There are innumerable statues, commemorations, books, and archival collections.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] The memory includes the home front, military affairs, the treatment of soldiers, both living and dead, in the war's aftermath, depictions of the war in literature and art, evaluations of heroes and villains, and considerations of the moral and political lessons of the war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] The last theme includes moral evaluations of racism and slavery, heroism and cowardice in combat and behind the lines, and issues of democracy and minority rights, as well as the notion of an "Empire of Liberty" influencing the world.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] Historians have paid great attention to the causes of the war as well as to the war itself.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] Military history has developed outside as well as inside academia, leading to a proliferation of studies by non-scholars who nevertheless are familiar with the primary sources and pay close attention to battles and campaigns and who write for the general public.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] Practically every major figure in the war, both North and South, has had a serious biographical study.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] Even the name used for the conflict has been controversial, with many names used for it.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] During and immediately after the war, Northern historians often used a term like "War of the Rebellion".
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] Writers in rebel states often referred to the "War for Southern Independence".
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] Some Southerners have described it as the "War of Northern Aggression".
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] The memory of the war in the white South crystallized in the myth of the "Lost Cause": that the Confederate cause was just and heroic.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] The myth shaped regional identity and race relations for generations.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] Nolan notes that the Lost Cause was expressly a rationalization, a cover-up to vindicate the name and fame of those in rebellion.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] Some claims revolve around the insignificance of slavery as a cause; some appeals highlight cultural differences between North and South; the military conflict by Confederate actors is idealized; in any case, secession was said to be lawful.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] Nolan argues that the adoption of the Lost Cause perspective facilitated the reunification of the North and the South while excusing the "virulent racism" of the 19th century, sacrificing black American progress to white man's reunification.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] He also deems the Lost Cause "a caricature of the truth.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] This caricature wholly misrepresents and distorts the facts of the matter" in every instance.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] The Lost Cause myth was formalized by Charles A.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] Beard, whose *The Rise of American Civilization* (1927) spawned Beardian historiography.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] The Beards downplayed slavery, abolitionism, and issues of morality.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] Though this interpretation was abandoned by the Beards in the 1940s, and by historians generally by the 1950s, Beardian themes still echo among Lost Cause writers.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] The first efforts at Civil War battlefield preservation and memorialization came during the war, with the establishment of National Cemeteries at Gettysburg, Mill Springs and Chattanooga.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] Soldiers began erecting markers on battlefields beginning with the First Battle of Bull Run in 1861.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] The oldest surviving monument is the Hazen Brigade Monument near Murfreesboro in Central Tennessee, built in the summer of 1863 by soldiers in Union Col.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] Hazen's brigade to mark the spot where they buried their dead, following the Battle of Stones River.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] The Shiloh National Military Park was established in 1894 in Shiloh, Tennessee, followed by the Gettysburg National Military Park in 1895, and Vicksburg National Military Park in 1899.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] In 1933, these five parks and other national monuments were transferred to the National Park Service.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] Chief among modern efforts to preserve Civil War sites has been the American Battlefield Trust, with more than 130 battlefields in 24 states.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] The five major battlefield parks operated by the National Park Service had a combined 3 million visitors in 2018, down 70% from 10 million in 1970.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] The Civil War has been commemorated in many ways, ranging from the reenactment of battles, to statues and memorial halls being erected, to films, and to stamps and coins with Civil War themes being issued, all of which helped to shape public memory.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] These commemorations occurred in greater numbers on the 100th and 150th anniversaries of the war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] Hollywood's take on the war has been especially influential in shaping public memory, as in such film classics as *The Birth of a Nation* (1915), *Gone with the Wind* (1939), and *Lincoln* (2012).
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] Ken Burns's PBS television series *The Civil War* (1990) is well-remembered, though criticized for its historical inaccuracy.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] Technological innovations during the war had a great impact on 19th-century science.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] The war was an early example of an "industrial war", in which technological might is used to achieve military supremacy.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] New inventions, such as the train and telegraph, delivered soldiers, supplies and messages at a time when horses had been the fastest way to travel.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] It was also in this war that aerial warfare, in the form of reconnaissance balloons, was first used.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] It saw the first action involving steam-powered ironclad warships in naval warfare history.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] Repeating firearms such as the Henry rifle, Spencer repeating rifle, Colt revolving rifle, Triplett & Scott carbine and others, first appeared during the Civil War; they were a revolutionary invention that would soon replace muzzle-loading and single-shot firearms.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] The war saw the first appearances of rapid-firing weapons and machine guns such as the Agar gun and Gatling gun.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] The Civil War is one of the most studied events in American history, and the collection of cultural works around it is enormous.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-civil-war-p03] This section gives an abbreviated overview of the most notable works.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The **American Revolution** (1765–1789) was a political movement in the Thirteen Colonies of Great Britain.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] It began as a rebellion and turned into a revolution eventually creating the sovereign United States, which was the outcome of the associated American Revolutionary War (1775-1783).
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The Second Continental Congress, as the provisional government, established the Continental Army and appointed George Washington as its commander-in-chief in 1775.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The following year, the Congress passed the Lee Resolution on July 2nd and unanimously adopted the Declaration of Independence on July 4th.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The Constitution took effect in 1789 and the Bill of Rights was ratified in 1791.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Discontent with colonial rule began shortly after the French and Indian War, which ended in 1763.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Although the colonies had fought and supported the war directly, the British Parliament imposed new taxes to compensate for wartime costs and transferred control of the colonies' western lands to British officials in Montreal.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Representatives from several colonies convened in New York City for the Stamp Act Congress in 1765.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Its declaration argued that taxation without representation and other policies violated their rights as Englishmen.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] In 1767, though the Stamp Act was repealed, tensions increased again following Parliament's passing of the Townshend Acts.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] In an effort to quell the mounting rebellion, King George III deployed British troops to the colony of Massachusetts, where there was a conflict in the 1770 Boston Massacre.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] In December 1773, the local faction of the Sons of Liberty orchestrated the Boston Tea Party, during which they dumped chests of taxed tea owned by the British East India Company into the Boston Harbor.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Parliament responded by enacting a series of punitive laws, called the Intolerable Acts.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] These were intended to end self-government in Massachusetts but instead increased American support for revolution.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] In 1774, 12 of the Thirteen Colonies sent delegates to the First Continental Congress (the Province of Georgia joined in 1775).
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The First Continental Congress began coordinating Patriot resistance through underground networks of committees largely built on the foundations of the Sons of Liberty network.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] In August 1775, King George III proclaimed Massachusetts to be in rebellion.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The British attempted to disarm the colonists, resulting in the Battles of Lexington and Concord, starting the Revolutionary War.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The Second Continental Congress convened in May of 1775 and created the Continental Army, which then surrounded Boston, forcing the British to withdraw by sea in March 1776 and leaving Patriots in control in every colony.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] In May 1776, Congress voted to suppress all forms of Crown authority to be replaced by locally created authority, and each colony created a state constitution.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] On July 2, the Congress passed the Lee Resolution, affirming their support for joint independence.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] On July 4, 1776, they unanimously adopted the Declaration of Independence, proclaiming that "all men are created equal".
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] After that, Congress began drafting the Articles of Confederation, an effort to establish a multi-state self-governing coordinating body capable of negotiating international treaties and prosecuting the war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The Revolutionary War continued for another five years, during which France eventually entered.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] On September 28, 1781, Washington commanded the Continental Army's capture of a British army under General Cornwallis at the Siege of Yorktown, leading to the collapse of King George's control of Parliament.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Consensus in Parliament soon shifted to the war ending on American terms.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] On September 3, 1783, the British signed the Treaty of Paris, recognizing the sovereign independence of the United States, and ceding to the new nation nearly all the territory east of the Mississippi River and south of the Great Lakes.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The United States became the first nation to establish a federal republic with a written constitution based on the principles of universal natural rights, consent of the governed, and equality under the law, although with significant democratic limitations compared to later evolution of the concept.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] After the Glorious Revolution in Great Britain, the Britain adopted a policy of "salutary neglect," whereby the Thirteen Colonies were largely left to govern themselves.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] This British policy reverted significantly after the French and Indian War.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The British political establishment, especially after taking massive swaths of land from the former territories of New France, pursued a policy of greater control over colonial affairs, prompting the Thirteen Colonies to seek restoration of greater autonomy from Britain.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] After the American Revolution one Patriot, Capt.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Levi Preston of Danvers, Massachusetts, who was asked why the Americans rebelled against England, responded: "...we always had governed ourselves, and we always meant to.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The Thirteen Colonies were established in the 17th century as part of the English Empire and became parts of the British Empire after the union of England and Scotland in 1707.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The development of a unique American identity can be traced to the English Civil War (1642–1651) and its aftermath.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] In that period the Puritan colonies of New England supported the Commonwealth government responsible for the execution of King Charles I.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] After the Stuart Restoration of 1660, Massachusetts did not recognize Charles II as the legitimate king for more than a year after his coronation.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] In King Philip's War (1675–1678), the New England colonies fought a coalition of a few Native American tribes without military assistance from England, thereby contributing to the development of a uniquely American identity separate from that of the British people.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] In the 1680s, Charles and his brother, James II, attempted to bring New England under direct English control.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The colonists fiercely opposed this, and the Crown nullified their colonial charters in response.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] In 1686, James finalized these efforts by consolidating the separate New England colonies along with New York and New Jersey into the Dominion of New England.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Edmund Andros was appointed royal governor and tasked with governing the new Dominion under his direct rule.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Colonial assemblies and town meetings were restricted, new local taxes were levied, and rights were abridged.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Dominion rule triggered bitter resentment throughout New England.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] When James tried to rule without Parliament, the English aristocracy removed him from power in the Glorious Revolution of 1688.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] This was followed by the 1689 Boston revolt, which overthrew Dominion rule.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Colonial governments reasserted their control after the revolt.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The new monarchs, William and Mary, granted new charters to the individual New England colonies.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] After the Glorious Revolution, the British Empire became a constitutional monarchy with sovereignty in the King-in-Parliament.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Aristocrats inherited seats in the House of Lords, while the gentry and merchants controlled the elected House of Commons.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The king ruled through cabinet ministers who depended on majority support in the Commons to govern effectively.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] British subjects on both sides of the Atlantic proudly claimed that the unwritten British constitution, with its guarantees of the rights of Englishmen, protected personal liberty better than any other government.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The British constitution served as the model for colonial governments.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The Crown appointed a royal governor in each colony to exercise executive power, usually also appointing a Governor's Council largely to act as an unelected upper chamber of the legislature.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Property owners elected a colonial assembly amongst themselves with powers to legislate and levy taxes, but the British government reserved the right to veto colonial legislation.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The British government lacked the resources and information necessary for close supervision of the colonies.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Instead, British officials negotiated and compromised with colonial leaders to gain compliance with imperial policies.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The colonies defended themselves with provincial troops and colonial militias of locals, and the British government rarely sent military forces to America before 1755.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] According to historian Robert Middlekauff, "Americans had become almost completely self-governing" before the American Revolution, a practice that was consistent with the British monarchy's practice of salutary neglect.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] With little industry except shipbuilding, the colonies exported agricultural products in return for manufactured goods.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] They also imported molasses, rum, and sugar from the British West Indies.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] In 1651, Parliament passed the first in a series of Navigation Acts, which restricted colonial trade with foreign countries.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The British government pursued this policy of mercantilism in order to grow its economic and political power.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] According to mercantilism, the colonies existed for the mother country's economic benefit, and the colonists' economic needs were largely inconsequential.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The Thirteen Colonies could trade with the rest of the empire but only ship certain commodities like tobacco to Britain.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Any European imports bound for British America had to first pass through an English port and pay customs duties.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Other laws regulated the developing colonial industries to prevent competition with industries in Britain, such as the Wool Act 1698, the Hat Act 1731, and the Iron Act 1750.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Colonial reactions to these policies were mixed.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The Molasses Act 1733, for example, placed a duty of six pence per gallon upon foreign molasses imported into the colonies.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] This act was particularly egregious to the New England colonists, who protested it as unconstitutional taxation without representation in the British parliament.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The act increased the smuggling of foreign molasses, and the British government ceased enforcement efforts after the 1740s.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] On the other hand, certain merchants and local industries benefited from the restrictions on foreign competition.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The limits on foreign-built ships greatly benefited the colonial shipbuilding industry, particularly in New England.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Some argue that the economic impact was minimal on the colonists, but the political friction that the acts triggered was more serious, as the merchants most directly affected were also the most politically active.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] During the French and Indian War (1754–1763), the British government fielded 45,000 soldiers, half British Regulars and half colonial volunteers.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The colonies also contributed funds and materiel to the war effort; though, two-fifths of this spending was reimbursed by the British government.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Great Britain defeated France and acquired that nation's territory east of the Mississippi River.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] In order to allow approximately 1,500 politically well-connected British Army officers to remain on active duty in America with full pay after the war, the Bute ministry decided in early 1763 to permanently garrison 10,000 soldiers in North America.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Due to long-established English resistance to a standing army, stationing these officers in Great Britain during peacetime was a politically unacceptable alternative.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The excuse made for a standing army in America was defense against French troops stationed in the West Indies, and foreign populations in newly acquired territories (the French in Canada and the Spanish in Florida).
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] In addition, British soldiers were supposed to help collect customs duties and prevent colonists from instigating conflict with Native Americans.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Instead, increased British migration beyond the Appalachian Mountains and Native American anger over the policies of General Jeffery Amherst caused Pontiac's War (1763–1766).
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] In response, the Grenville ministry issued the Royal Proclamation of 1763, designating the territory between the Appalachian Mountains and the Mississippi River an Indian Reserve closed to colonial settlement.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The Proclamation angered settlers, fur traders, and land speculators; however, it failed to stop westward migration.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Stationing troops in North America on a permanent basis would cost another £360,000 a year.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] On a per capita basis, Grenville claimed Americans paid 1 shilling in taxes directly to the empire (not including local taxes) compared to 26 shillings paid by the English.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The enslaved, a near majority of the population in some colonies, did not pay any taxes and therefore skewed this comparison.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] On March 9, 1764, Grenville proposed the Sugar Act, which was enacted by Parliament in April.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] It lowered the duty on foreign molasses from 6 pence to 3 pence per gallon.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The Treasury believed it would generate £78,000.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] To ensure this money could be collected, the act strengthened efforts against smuggling.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Customs officials could choose whether to prosecute violators in colonial courts or vice admiralty courts.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Unlike colonial courts where there was a presumption of innocence and cases were decided by local juries who frequently acquitted accused smugglers, vice admiralty courts operated on a presumption of guilt and cases were decided by Crown-appointed judges.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] On the same day he introduced the Sugar Act in Parliament, Grenville stated it might be necessary to levy stamp duties on the colonies to raise additional revenue, but he delayed action to give the colonies time to propose another way to raise the revenue.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Parliament passed the Stamp Act in March 1765, which imposed direct taxes on the colonies for the first time.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] All official documents, newspapers, almanacs, and pamphlets were required to have the stamps—even decks of playing cards.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The colonists did not object that the taxes were high; they were actually low.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] They objected to their lack of representation in the Parliament, which gave them no voice concerning legislation that affected them, such as the tax, thereby violating the unwritten English constitution.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] This grievance was overly simplified with the slogan "No taxation without representation".
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Shortly following adoption of the Stamp Act, factions of the Sons of Liberty formed in each colony, and began using public demonstrations, boycotts, and threats of violence to ensure that the offending British policies became unenforceable.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] In Boston, the Sons of Liberty burned the records of the vice admiralty court and looted the home of chief justice Thomas Hutchinson.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Several legislatures called for united action, and nine colonies sent delegates to the Stamp Act Congress in New York City in October.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Moderates led by John Dickinson drew up a Declaration of Rights and Grievances stating in part that the colonists were equal to all other British subjects and that, among other abuses, taxes passed without representation in Parliament violated their rights as Englishmen.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The Parliament at Westminster saw itself as the supreme lawmaking authority throughout the Empire and thus entitled to enact any legislation, including levying any tax, without colonial approval or even consultation.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] They argued that the colonies were legally British corporations subordinate to the British Parliament.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Parliament insisted that the colonists effectively enjoyed a "virtual representation", as most British people did, since only a small minority of the British population were eligible to elect representatives to Parliament.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] However, Americans such as James Otis maintained that there was no one in Parliament responsible specifically to any colonial constituency, so they were not "virtually represented" by anyone in Parliament.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The Rockingham government came to power in July 1765, and Parliament debated whether to repeal the stamp tax or to send an army to enforce it.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Benjamin Franklin appeared before them to make the case for repeal, explaining that the colonies had spent heavily in manpower, money, and blood defending the empire, and that further taxes to pay for those wars were unjust and might bring about a rebellion.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Parliament agreed and repealed the tax on February 21, 1766, but they insisted in the Declaratory Act of March 1766 that they retained full power to make laws for the colonies "in all cases whatsoever".
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The repeal nonetheless caused widespread celebrations in the colonies.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] In 1767, the British Parliament passed the Townshend Acts, which placed duties on several staple goods, including paper, glass, and tea, and established a Board of Customs in Boston to more rigorously execute trade regulations.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The new taxes were enacted on the belief that Americans only objected to internal taxes and not to external taxes such as custom duties.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] John Dickinson however, in his widely read pamphlet *Letters from a Farmer in Pennsylvania*, argued against the constitutionality of the acts because their purpose was to raise revenue and not to regulate trade.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Colonists responded to the taxes by organizing new boycotts of British goods.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] These boycotts were less effective, however, as the goods taxed by the Townshend Acts were widely used.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] In February 1768, the Assembly of Massachusetts Bay Colony issued a circular letter to the other colonies urging them to coordinate resistance.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The governor dissolved the assembly when it refused to rescind the letter.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] In June 1768 a riot broke out in Boston over the seizure of the sloop *Liberty*, owned by John Hancock, for alleged smuggling.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Customs officials were forced to flee, prompting the British to deploy troops to Boston.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] A Boston town meeting declared that no obedience was due to parliamentary laws and called for the convening of a convention.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] A convention assembled but only issued a mild protest before dissolving itself.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] In January 1769, Parliament responded to the unrest by reactivating the Treason Act 1543 which called for subjects outside the realm to face trials for treason in England.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The governor of Massachusetts was instructed to collect evidence of said treason, and the threat caused widespread outrage, though it was not carried out.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] On March 5, 1770, a large crowd gathered around a group of British soldiers on a Boston street.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The crowd grew threatening, throwing snowballs, rocks, and debris at them.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] There was no order to fire, but the soldiers panicked and fired into the crowd.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] They hit 11 people; three civilians died of wounds at the scene of the shooting, and two died shortly after.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The event quickly came to be called the Boston Massacre.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The soldiers were tried and acquitted (defended by American patriot John Adams), but the widespread descriptions soon began to turn colonial sentiment against the British.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] This accelerated the downward spiral in the relationship between Britain and the province of Massachusetts, and other colonies were becoming increasingly empathetic.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] A new ministry under Lord North came to power in 1770, and Parliament repealed most of the Townshend duties, except the tax on tea.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] This temporarily resolved the crisis, and the boycott of British goods largely ceased, with only the more radical patriots such as Samuel Adams continuing to agitate.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] In June 1772, American patriots, including John Brown, burned a British warship that had been vigorously enforcing unpopular trade regulations, in what became known as the *Gaspee* Affair.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The affair was investigated for possible treason, but no action was taken.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] In 1773, private letters were published in which Massachusetts Governor Thomas Hutchinson claimed that the colonists could not enjoy all English liberties, and in which Lieutenant Governor Andrew Oliver called for the direct payment of colonial officials, which had been paid by local authorities.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] This would have reduced the influence of colonial representatives over their government.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The letters' contents were used as evidence of a systematic plot against American rights, and discredited Hutchinson in the eyes of the people; the colonial Assembly petitioned for his recall.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Benjamin Franklin, postmaster general for the colonies, acknowledged that he leaked the letters, which led to him being removed from his position.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] From Boston Samuel Adams set about creating new Committees of Correspondence, built largely on the foundations of the underground Sons of Liberty network, linking Patriots in all 13 colonies and eventually providing the framework for a provisional government.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Virginia, the largest colony, set up its Committee of Correspondence in early 1773, on which Patrick Henry and Thomas Jefferson served.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] A total of about 7,000 to 8,000 Patriots served on these Committees; Loyalists were excluded.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The committees became the leaders of the American resistance to British actions, and later largely determined the war effort at the state and local level.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] When the First Continental Congress resolved to boycott British products, the colonial and local Committees took charge, examining merchant records and publishing the names of merchants who attempted to defy the boycott by importing British goods.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Meanwhile, Parliament passed the Tea Act lowering the price of taxed tea exported to the colonies, to help the British East India Company undersell smuggled untaxed Dutch tea.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Special consignees were appointed to sell the tea to bypass colonial merchants.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The act was opposed by those who resisted the taxes and also by smugglers who stood to lose business.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] In every colony demonstrators warned merchants not to bring in tea that included the hated new tax.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] In most instances, the consignees were forced by the Americans to resign and the tea was turned back, but Massachusetts governor Hutchinson refused to allow Boston merchants to give in to pressure.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] A town meeting in Boston determined that the tea would not be landed, and ignored a demand from the governor to disperse.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] On December 16, 1773, a group of men, led by Samuel Adams and dressed to evoke the appearance of Indigenous people, boarded the ships of the East India Company and dumped £10,000 worth of tea from their holds (approximately £636,000 in 2008) into Boston Harbor.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Decades later, this event became known as the Boston Tea Party and remains a significant part of American patriotic lore.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The British government responded by passing four laws that came to be known as the Intolerable Acts, further darkening colonial opinion towards England.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The first was the Massachusetts Government Act which altered the Massachusetts charter and restricted town meetings.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The second was the Administration of Justice Act which ordered that all British soldiers to be tried were to be arraigned in Britain, not in the colonies.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The third was the Boston Port Act, which closed the port of Boston until the British had been compensated for the tea lost in the Boston Tea Party.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The fourth was the Quartering Act of 1774, which allowed royal governors to house British troops in the homes of citizens without permission of the owner.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] In response, "Starting in August 1774, each time a court was slated to meet in some Massachusetts town, great numbers of angry citizens made sure it did not".
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The next month Patriots issued the Suffolk Resolves and formed an alternative shadow cabinet known as the Massachusetts Provincial Congress, which began training militia outside British-occupied Boston.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] In September 1774, the First Continental Congress convened in Pennsylvania, consisting of representatives from each colony, to serve as a vehicle for deliberation and collective action.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] During secret debates, conservative Joseph Galloway proposed the creation of a colonial Parliament that would be able to approve or disapprove acts of the British Parliament, but his idea was tabled in a vote of 6 to 5 and was subsequently removed from the record.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Congress called for a boycott beginning on December 1, 1774, of all British goods; it was enforced by new local committees authorized by the Congress that were largely built upon the earlier Committees of Correspondence.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] It also began coordinating Patriot resistance by militias in each colony, including many veterans who had gained military experience in the French and Indian War.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] For the first time, the Patriots were armed and unified against Parliament.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] King George III declared Massachusetts to be in a state of rebellion in February 1775 and the British garrison received orders to seize the rebels' weapons and arrest their leaders, resulting in the Battles of Lexington and Concord on April 19, 1775.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The Patriots assembled a militia 15,000 strong and laid siege to Boston, occupied by 6500 British soldiers.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The Second Continental Congress convened in Philadelphia on June 14, 1775.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The congress was divided on the best course of action.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] They authorized formation of the Continental Army, appointing George Washington as its commander-in-chief, while producing the Olive Branch Petition in which they attempted to come to an accord with King George.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The king, however, would issue a Proclamation of Rebellion in August which declared that all the states were "in rebellion" and the members of Congress were traitors.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Meanwhile, the Battle of Bunker Hill on June 17, 1775 was a British victory—but at a great cost: about 1,000 British casualties from a garrison of about 6,000, as compared to 500 American casualties from a much larger force.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] In the winter of 1775, the Americans invaded northeastern Quebec under generals Benedict Arnold and Richard Montgomery.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The attack was a failure; many Americans were killed, captured, or died of smallpox.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Following the Battle of Bunker Hill in June 1775, the Patriots had control of Massachusetts outside Boston's city limits, and the Loyalists suddenly found themselves on the defensive with no protection from the British army.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] In each of the Thirteen Colonies, American patriots overthrew their existing governments, closed courts, and drove out British colonial officials.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] They held elected conventions and established their own legislatures, which existed outside any legal parameters established by the British.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] New constitutions were drawn up in each state to supersede royal charters.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] They proclaimed that they were now *states*, no longer *colonies*.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] On January 5, 1776, New Hampshire ratified the first state constitution.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] In May 1776, Congress voted to suppress all forms of Crown authority, to be replaced by locally created authority.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] New Jersey, South Carolina, and Virginia created their constitutions before July 4.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Rhode Island and Connecticut simply took their existing royal charters and deleted all references to the Crown.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The new states were all committed to republicanism, with no inherited offices.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The radical provisions of Pennsylvania's constitution lasted 14 years.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] In 1790, conservatives gained power in the state legislature, called a new constitutional convention, and rewrote the constitution.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The new constitution substantially reduced universal male suffrage, gave the governor veto power and patronage appointment authority, and added an upper house with substantial wealth qualifications to the unicameral legislature.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Thomas Paine called it a constitution unworthy of America.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] In March 1776, aided by the fortification of Dorchester Heights with cannons recently captured at Fort Ticonderoga, the Continental Army led by George Washington forced the British to evacuate Boston.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The revolutionaries now fully controlled all thirteen states and ready to declare joint independence.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] There still were many Loyalists, but they were no longer in control anywhere by July 1776, and all of the royal officials had fled.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] In April 1776, the North Carolina Provincial Congress issued the Halifax Resolves explicitly authorizing its delegates to vote for independence.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] By June, nine state legislatures supported independence from Britain, and Pennsylvania, Delaware, Maryland, and New York followed.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Richard Henry Lee was instructed by the Virginia legislature to propose independence, and he did so on June 7, 1776.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Gathered at Pennsylvania State House in Philadelphia, later renamed Independence Hall, 56 of the nation's Founding Fathers representing the United Colonies adopted and issued to King George III the Declaration of Independence.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] It had been drafted largely by Thomas Jefferson, and was edited and presented by the Committee of Five which was charged with authoring it.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The Congress struck several provisions of the Committee's draft, and then adopted it unanimously on July 4.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The Declaration embodied universal rights expressed through the political philosophies of liberalism and republicanism, rejected monarchy and aristocracy, and famously proclaimed that "all men are created equal".
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] What had begun as a rebellion demanding the rights of Englishmen had now evolved into a revolution to overthrow and replace the political and social order in America based on universal rights.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] With the new state constitutions and the issuance of the Declaration of Independence, each former colony began operating as an independent and sovereign state.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The next step was to form a union to facilitate international relations and alliances.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] On November 5, 1777, the Congress approved the Articles of Confederation and Perpetual Union and sent it to each state for ratification.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The Congress immediately began operating under the Articles' terms, providing a structure of shared sovereignty during prosecution of the Revolutionary War.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The Articles were fully ratified on March 1, 1781.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] At that point, the Continental Congress was dissolved and a new government of the United States in Congress Assembled took its place the following day, with Samuel Huntington leading the Congress as presiding officer.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] It remained a unicameral body, where each state retained one vote.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] According to British historian Jeremy Black, the British had significant advantages, including a highly trained army, the world's largest navy, and an efficient system of public finance that could easily fund the war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] However, they seriously misunderstood the depth of support for the American Patriot position, misinterpreting the situation as merely a large-scale riot.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] In the Siege of Boston, Washington forced the British out of the city in the spring of 1776, and neither the British nor the Loyalists controlled any significant areas.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The British, however, were amassing forces at their naval base at Halifax, Nova Scotia.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] They returned in force in July 1776, landing in New York and defeating Washington's Continental Army toe-to-toe in August at the Battle of Brooklyn, the largest battle of the war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Following that victory, and poised to take New York City, they requested a meeting with representatives from Congress to negotiate an end to hostilities.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] A delegation including John Adams and Benjamin Franklin met British admiral Richard Howe on Staten Island in New York Harbor on September 11 in what became known as the Staten Island Peace Conference.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Howe demanded that the Americans retract the Declaration of Independence, which they refused to do, and negotiations ended.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The British then seized New York City and nearly captured Washington's army.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] They made the city their main political and military base of operations, holding the strategic harbor and port until November 1783.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The city became the destination for Loyalist refugees and a focal point of Washington's intelligence network.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The British also took New Jersey, pushing the Continental Army into Pennsylvania.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Washington crossed the Delaware River back into New Jersey in a surprise attack in late December 1776 and defeated the Hessian and British garrisons at Trenton and Princeton, thereby regaining control of most of New Jersey.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The victories gave an important boost to Patriots at a time when morale was flagging and enlistments were ending, and they have become iconic events of the war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] In 1777, the British sent Burgoyne's invasion force from Canada south through New York with the aim of isolating New England to the east, which the British perceived as the primary source of agitation.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] In anticipation of a coordinated British attack on the *de facto* revolutionary capital of Philadelphia, the Continental Congress was forced to temporarily depart Philadelphia in September for Baltimore, where they continued deliberations.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Rather than move north to support Burgoyne, the British army in New York City in fact went to Philadelphia in a major case of mis-coordination, capturing it from Washington.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The invasion army from Canada was much too slow and became trapped in northern New York state.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] It surrendered to the Americans after the Battles of Saratoga in October 1777.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] From early October 1777 until November 15, a siege distracted British troops at Fort Mifflin, Pennsylvania and allowed Washington time to preserve the Continental Army by safely leading his troops to harsh winter quarters at Valley Forge, some 35 miles from Philadelphia.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] On August 23, 1775, George III declared Americans to be traitors to the Crown if they took up arms against royal authority.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] There were thousands of British and Hessian soldiers in American hands following their surrender at the Battles of Saratoga.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Lord Germain took a hard line, but the British generals on American soil never held treason trials, and instead treated captured American soldiers as prisoners of war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The dilemma was that tens of thousands of Loyalists were under American control and American retaliation would have been easy.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The British built much of their strategy around using these Loyalists.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The British maltreated the prisoners whom they held, resulting in more American deaths in the prisons than all the American battlefield mortalities, combined.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] At the end of the war, both sides released their surviving prisoners.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The capture of a British army at Saratoga encouraged the French to formally enter the war in support of Congress, and Benjamin Franklin negotiated a permanent military alliance in early 1778; France thus became the first foreign nation to officially recognize the Declaration of Independence.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] On February 6, 1778, the United States and France signed the Treaty of Amity and Commerce and the Treaty of Alliance.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] William Pitt spoke out in Parliament urging Britain to make peace with the Americans and to unite against France, while British politicians who had sympathized with colonial grievances now turned against the Americans for allying with Britain's rival and enemy.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The Spanish and the Dutch became allies of the French in 1779 and 1780 respectively, forcing the British to fight a global war without major allies, and requiring it to slip through a combined blockade of the Atlantic.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The Dutch Republic, also at war with Britain, was the next country after France to sign a treaty with the United States, on October 8, 1782.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] On April 3, 1783, Ambassador Extraordinary Gustaf Philip Creutz, representing King Gustav III of Sweden, and Benjamin Franklin, signed a Treaty of Amity and Commerce with the U.S.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Britain began to view the American Revolutionary War as merely one front in a wider war, and the British chose to withdraw troops from America to reinforce the British colonies in the Caribbean, which were under threat of Spanish or French invasion.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] British commander Sir Henry Clinton evacuated Philadelphia and returned to New York City.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Washington intercepted him in the Battle of Monmouth Court House, the last major battle fought in the north.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] After an inconclusive engagement, the British retreated to New York City.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The northern war subsequently became a stalemate, as the focus of attention shifted to the smaller southern theater.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The British Royal Navy blockaded ports and held New York City for the duration of the war, and other cities for brief periods, but failed in their effort to destroy Washington's forces.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The British strategy now concentrated on a campaign in the southern states.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Due to a lack of regular troops at their disposal compared to the Americans, the British commanders saw the "southern strategy" as a more viable plan.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] They perceived the Southern Colonies as strongly Loyalist, with a large population of recent British immigrants, and large numbers of slaves who might be tempted to run away from their Patriot masters to join the British and gain their freedom.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Beginning in late December 1778, the British captured Savannah and controlled the Georgia coastline.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] In 1780, they launched a fresh invasion and took Charleston.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] A significant victory at the Battle of Camden meant that royal forces soon controlled most of Georgia and South Carolina.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The British set up a network of forts inland, hoping that the Loyalists would rally to the flag.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Not enough Loyalists turned out, however, and the British had to fight their way north into North Carolina and Virginia with a severely weakened army.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Behind them, much of the territory that they had already captured dissolved into a chaotic guerrilla war, fought predominantly between bands of Loyalists and American militia, which negated many of the gains that the British had previously made.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The British army under Cornwallis marched to Yorktown, Virginia, where they expected to be rescued by a British fleet.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The fleet did arrive, but so did a larger French fleet.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The French were victorious in the Battle of the Chesapeake, and the British fleet returned to New York for reinforcements, leaving Cornwallis trapped.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] In October 1781, the British surrendered their second invading army of the war under a siege by the combined French and Continental armies commanded by Washington.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Washington did not know if or when the British might reopen hostilities after Yorktown.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] They still had 26,000 troops occupying New York City, Charleston, and Savannah, together with a powerful fleet.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The French army and navy departed, so the Americans were on their own in 1782–83.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The American treasury was empty, and the unpaid soldiers were growing restive, almost to the point of mutiny or possible coup d'etat.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Washington dispelled the unrest among officers of the Newburgh Conspiracy in 1783, and Congress subsequently created the promise of a five years bonus for all officers.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Historians continue to debate whether the odds were long or short for American victory.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Ferling says that the odds were so long that the American victory was "almost a miracle".
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] On the other hand, Joseph Ellis says that the odds favored the Americans, and asks whether there ever was any realistic chance for the British to win.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] He argues that this opportunity came only once, in the summer of 1776, where Admiral Howe and his brother General Howe "missed several opportunities to destroy the Continental Army ....
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Chance, luck, and even the vagaries of the weather played crucial roles." Ellis's point is that the strategic and tactical decisions of the Howes were fatally flawed because they underestimated the challenges posed by the Patriots.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Ellis concludes that, once the Howe brothers failed, the opportunity "would never come again" for a British victory.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Public support for the conflict had never been strong in Britain, where many sympathized with the Americans, but now it reached a new low.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] King George wanted to fight on, but his supporters lost control of Parliament and the British launched no further offensives in America on the eastern seaboard.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] During negotiations in Paris, the American delegation discovered that France supported American independence but no territorial gains, hoping to confine the new nation to the area east of the Appalachian Mountains.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The Americans opened direct secret negotiations with London, cutting out the French.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] British Prime Minister Lord Shelburne was in charge of the British negotiations, and he saw a chance to make the United States a valuable economic partner, facilitating trade and investment opportunities.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The US obtained all the land east of the Mississippi River, including southern Canada below the Great Lakes, but Spain took control of Florida from the British.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] It gained fishing rights off Canadian coasts, and agreed to allow British merchants and Loyalists to recover their property.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] Prime Minister Shelburne foresaw highly profitable two-way trade between Britain and the rapidly growing United States, which did come to pass.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The blockade was lifted and American merchants were free to trade with any nation anywhere in the world.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] The British largely abandoned their Indigenous allies, who were not a party to this treaty and did not recognize it until they were defeated militarily by the United States.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p01] However, the British did sell them munitions and maintained forts in American territory until the Jay Treaty of 1795.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Britain's war against the Americans, the French, and the Spanish cost about £100 million.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The Treasury borrowed 40 percent of the money that it needed.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Britain had a sophisticated financial system based on the wealth of thousands of landowners who supported the government, together with banks and financiers in London.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] In London the British had relatively little difficulty financing their war, keeping their suppliers and soldiers paid, and hiring tens of thousands of German soldiers.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] In sharp contrast, Congress and the American states had no end of difficulty financing the war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] In 1775, there was at most 12 million dollars in gold in the colonies, not nearly enough to cover current transactions, let alone finance a major war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The British made the situation much worse by imposing a tight blockade on every American port, which cut off almost all trade.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] One partial solution was to rely on volunteer support from militiamen and donations from patriotic citizens.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Another was to delay actual payments, pay soldiers and suppliers in depreciated currency, and promise that it would be made good after the war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Indeed, the soldiers and officers were given land grants in 1783 to cover the wages that they had earned but had not been paid during the war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Starting in 1776, the Congress sought to raise money by loans from wealthy individuals, promising to redeem the bonds after the war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The bonds were redeemed in 1791 at face value, but the scheme raised little money because Americans had little specie, and many of the richest merchants were supporters of the Crown.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Beginning in 1777, Congress repeatedly asked the states to provide money, but it had no system of taxation to require funds, and the states were of little help.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] By 1780, Congress was making requisitions for specific supplies of corn, beef, pork, and other necessities, an inefficient system which barely kept the army alive.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Congress used four main methods to cover the cost of the war, which cost about 66 million dollars in specie (gold and silver).
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Significantly, the French secretly supplied the Americans with money, gunpowder, and munitions to weaken Great Britain; the subsidies continued when France entered the war in 1778, and the French government and Paris bankers lent large sums to the American war effort.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Congress also made issues of paper money, known colloquially as "Continental Dollars", in 1775–1780 and in 1780–1781.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The first issue amounted to 242 million dollars.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] This paper money would supposedly be redeemed for state taxes, but the holders were eventually paid off in 1791 at the rate of one cent on the dollar.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] By 1780, the paper money was so devalued that the phrase "not worth a Continental" became synonymous with valueless.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The skyrocketing inflation was a hardship on the few people who had fixed incomes, but 90 percent of the people were farmers and were not directly affected by it.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Debtors benefited by paying off their debts with depreciated paper.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The greatest burden was borne by the soldiers of the Continental Army whose wages were usually paid late and depreciated in value every month, weakening their morale and adding to the hardships of their families.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The national government did not have a strong leader in financial matters until 1781, when Robert Morris was named Superintendent of Finance of the United States.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Morris used a French loan in 1782 to set up the private Bank of North America to finance the war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] He reduced the civil list, saved money by using competitive bidding for contracts, tightened accounting procedures, and demanded the national government's full share of money and supplies from the individual states.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The war ended in 1783 and was followed by a period of slow economic recovery that accompanied the end of mercantilism and the resumption and expansion of worldwide trade.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The national government was still operating under the Articles of Confederation and settled the issue of the western territories, which the states ceded to Congress.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] American settlers moved rapidly into those areas, with Vermont, Kentucky, and Tennessee becoming states in the 1790s.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] However, the national government had no authority to tax, no money either to pay the war debts owed to European nations and the private banks, or to pay Americans who had been given millions of dollars of promissory notes for supplies during the war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Nationalists led by Washington, Alexander Hamilton, and other veterans feared that the new nation was too fragile to withstand an international war, or even the repetition of internal revolts such as the Shays's Rebellion of 1786 in Massachusetts.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] They convinced the Congress of the Confederation to call the Philadelphia Convention in 1787.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The Convention adopted a new Constitution which provided for a republic with authority to tax and a much stronger national government in a federal framework, including an effective executive in a check-and-balance system with the judiciary and legislature.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The Constitution was ratified in 1788, after a fierce debate in the states over the proposed new government.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The new administration under President George Washington took office in New York in March 1789 and the new bicameral Congress of the United States was seated.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] James Madison spearheaded Congressional legislation proposing amendments to the Constitution as assurances to those cautious about federal power, guaranteeing many of the inalienable rights that formed a foundation for the revolution.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Rhode Island was the final state to ratify the Constitution in 1790, the first ten amendments were ratified in 1791 and became known as the United States Bill of Rights.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The national debt fell into three categories after the Revolutionary War.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The first was the $12 million owed to foreigners, mostly money borrowed from France.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] There was general agreement to pay the foreign debts at full value.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The national government owed $40 million and state governments owed $25 million to Americans who had sold food, horses, and supplies to the Patriot forces.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] There were also other debts which consisted of promissory notes issued during the war to soldiers, merchants, and farmers who accepted these payments on the premise that the new nation would create a government that would pay these debts eventually.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The Americans struggled to pay off the French loans; they ceased making interest payments to France in 1785 and defaulted on installments due in 1787.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] In 1790, however, they resumed regular payments on their debts to the French.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The war expenses of the individual states added up to $114 million, compared to $37 million by the central government.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] In 1790, Congress combined the remaining state debts with the foreign and domestic debts into one national debt totaling $80 million at the recommendation of first Secretary of the Treasury Alexander Hamilton.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Everyone received face value for wartime certificates, so that the national honor would be sustained and the national credit established.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Accounts with the French government were settled in 1795 when James Swan, an American banker acting as agent for France, helped refinance the United States’ remaining debt to France.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The American government issued bonds in the amount of the remaining debt and sold them publicly, with the proceeds going to France through Swan.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The United States no longer owed money to foreign governments, although it continued to owe money to private investors both in the United States and in Europe..
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] This allowed the young United States to place itself on a sound financial footing.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The population of the Thirteen States was not homogeneous in political views and attitudes.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Loyalties and allegiances varied widely within regions and communities and even within families, and sometimes shifted during the Revolution.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The American Enlightenment was a critical precursor of the American Revolution.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Chief among the ideas of the American Enlightenment were the concepts of natural law, natural rights, consent of the governed, self-determination, equality under the law, liberalism, republicanism, and intolerance of political corruption.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] A growing number of American colonists embraced these views and fostered an intellectual environment which led to a new sense of political and social identity.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] John Locke is often referred to as "the philosopher of the American Revolution" due to his work in the Social Contract and Natural Rights theories that underpinned the Revolution's political ideology.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Locke's *Two Treatises of Government* published in 1689 was especially influential.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] He argued that all humans were created equally free, and governments therefore needed the "consent of the governed".
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] This contrasted and conflicted sharply with the British system of inherited political power and hierarchy.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] In late eighteenth-century America, belief was still widespread in "equality by creation" and "rights by creation".
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Locke's ideas on liberty influenced the political thinking of English writers such as John Trenchard, Thomas Gordon, and Benjamin Hoadly, whose political ideas in turn also had a strong influence on the American Patriots.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] His work also inspired symbols used in the American Revolution such as the "Appeal to Heaven" found on the Pine Tree Flag, which alludes to Locke's concept of the right of revolution.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The theory of the social contract influenced the belief among many of the Founders that the right of the people to overthrow their leaders, should those leaders betray the historic rights of Englishmen, was one of the "natural rights" of man.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The Americans heavily relied on Montesquieu's analysis of the wisdom of the "balanced" British Constitution (mixed government) in writing the state and national constitutions.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The American interpretation of republicanism was inspired by the Whig party in Great Britain which openly criticized the corruption within the British government.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Americans were increasingly embracing republican values, seeing Britain as corrupt and hostile to American interests.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Radical Whig ideology profoundly influenced colonial American political philosophy with its love of liberty and opposition to tyrannical government.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The American revolutionaries associated political corruption with ostentatious luxury and inherited aristocracy.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The Founding Fathers were strong advocates of republican values, particularly Samuel Adams, Patrick Henry, John Adams, Benjamin Franklin, Thomas Jefferson, Thomas Paine, George Washington, James Madison, and Alexander Hamilton, which required men to put civic duty ahead of their personal desires.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Men were honor bound by civic obligation to be prepared and willing to fight for the rights and liberties of their countrymen.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Protestant churches that had separated from the Church of England, called "dissenters", were the "school of democracy", in the words of historian Patricia Bonomi.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Before the Revolution, the Southern Colonies and three of the New England Colonies had official established churches: Congregational in Massachusetts Bay, Connecticut, and New Hampshire, and the Church of England in Maryland, Virginia, North-Carolina, South Carolina, and Georgia.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The colonies of New York, New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Delaware, and the Colony of Rhode Island and Providence Plantations had no officially established churches.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] John Witherspoon, who was considered a "new light" Presbyterian, wrote widely circulated sermons linking the American Revolution to the teachings of the Bible.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Throughout the colonies, dissenting Protestant ministers from the Congregational, Baptist, and Presbyterian churches preached Revolutionary themes in their sermons while most Church of England clergymen preached loyalty to the king, the titular head of the English state church.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Religious motivation for fighting tyranny transcended socioeconomic lines.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Historian Bernard Bailyn argues that the evangelicalism of the era challenged traditional notions of natural hierarchy by preaching that the Bible teaches all men are equal, and the true value of a man therefore lies in his moral behavior, not in his class.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Bailyn, on the other hand, denies that religion played such a critical role.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Alan Heimert argues that New Light anti-authoritarianism was essential to furthering democracy in colonial American society, and set the stage for a confrontation with British monarchical and aristocratic rule.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Historians in the early 20th century such as J.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Franklin Jameson examined the class composition of the Patriot cause, looking for evidence of a class war inside the revolution.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] More recent historians have largely abandoned that interpretation, emphasizing instead the high level of ideological unity.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Both Loyalists and Patriots were a "mixed lot", but ideological demands always came first.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The revolution became a personal issue for the king, fueled by his growing belief that British leniency would be taken as weakness by the Americans.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] He also sincerely believed that he was defending Britain's constitution against usurpers, rather than opposing patriots fighting for their natural rights.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] King George III is often accused of obstinately trying to keep Great Britain at war with the revolutionaries in America, despite the opinions of his own ministers.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Later historians defend George by saying in the context of the times no king would willingly surrender such a large territory, and his conduct was far less ruthless than contemporary monarchs in Europe.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] After the surrender of a British army at Saratoga, both Parliament and the British people were largely in favor of the war; recruitment ran at high levels and although political opponents were vocal, they remained a small minority.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] With the early setbacks in America, Lord North asked to transfer power to Lord Chatham, whom he thought more capable, but George refused to do so; he suggested instead that Chatham serve as a subordinate minister in North's administration, but Chatham refused.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Lord North was allied to the "King's Friends" faction in Parliament and believed George III had the right to exercise extensive powers.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] In early 1778, Britain's chief rival France signed a treaty of alliance with the United States, and the confrontation soon escalated from a "rebellion" to something that has been characterized as "world war".
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The French fleet was able to outrun the British naval blockade of the Mediterranean and sailed to North America.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The conflict now affected North America, Europe and India.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The United States and France were joined by Spain in 1779 and the Dutch Republic, while Britain had no major allies of its own, except for the Loyalist minority in America and German auxiliaries (i.e.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Lord Gower and Lord Weymouth both resigned from the government.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Lord North again requested that he also be allowed to resign, but he stayed in office at George III's insistence.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Opposition to the costly war was increasing, and in June 1780 contributed to disturbances in London known as the Gordon riots.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] As late as the Siege of Charleston in 1780, Loyalists could still believe in their eventual victory, as British troops inflicted defeats on the Continental forces at the Battle of Camden and the Battle of Guilford Court House.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] In late 1781, the news of Cornwallis's surrender at the siege of Yorktown reached London; Lord North's parliamentary support ebbed away and he resigned the following year.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The king drafted an abdication notice, which was never delivered, finally accepted the defeat in North America, and authorized peace negotiations.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The Treaties of Paris, by which Britain recognized the sovereignty of the United States and returned Florida to Spain, were signed in 1782 and 1783 respectively.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] In early 1783, George III privately conceded "America is lost!" He reflected that the former colonies had developed into Britain's "successful rivals" in commercial trade and fishing as the United States.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] When John Adams was appointed American Minister to London in 1785, George had become resigned to the new relationship between his country and the former colonies.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Those who fought for independence were called "Revolutionaries", "Continentals", "Rebels", "Patriots", "Whigs", "Congress-men", or "Americans" during and after the war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] They included a full range of social and economic classes but were unanimous regarding the need to defend the natural rights of Americans and uphold the principles of republicanism in rejecting monarchy and aristocracy, while emphasizing civic virtue by citizens.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The signers of the Declaration of Independence were overwhelmingly—with definite exceptions—well-educated, of British stock, and of the Protestant faith.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Newspapers were strongholds of patriotism (although there were a few Loyalist papers) and printed many pamphlets, announcements, patriotic letters, and pronouncements.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] According to historian Robert Calhoon, 40 to 45 percent of the white population in the Thirteen Colonies supported the Patriots' cause, 15 to 20 percent supported the Loyalists, and the remainder were neutral or kept a low profile.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Mark Lender concludes that ordinary people became insurgents against the British because they held a sense of rights which the British were violating, rights that stressed local autonomy, fair dealing, and government by consent.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] They were highly sensitive to the issue of tyranny, which they saw manifested in the British response to the Boston Tea Party.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The arrival in Boston of the British Army heightened their sense of violated rights, leading to rage and demands for revenge.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] They had faith that God was on their side.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The Patriots viewed independence as a means to gain freedom from British oppression and initially to reassert their rights on par with subjects in Britain.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Most yeomen farmers, craftsmen, and small merchants joined the Patriot cause to demand more political equality.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] They were especially successful in Pennsylvania but less so in New England, where John Adams attacked Thomas Paine's *Common Sense* for the "absurd democratical notions" that it proposed.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Thomas Paine published his pamphlet *Common Sense* in January 1776, after the Revolution had started.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] It was widely distributed and often read aloud in taverns, contributing significantly to concurrently spreading the ideas of republicanism and liberalism, bolstering enthusiasm for separation from Great Britain, and encouraging recruitment for the Continental Army.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Paine presented the Revolution as the solution for Americans alarmed by the threat of tyranny.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The consensus of scholars is that about 15 to 20 percent of the white population remained loyal to the British Crown.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Those who actively supported the king were known at the time as "Loyalists", "Tories", or "King's men".
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The Loyalists never controlled territory unless the British Army occupied it.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] They were typically older, less willing to break with old loyalties, and often connected to the Church of England; they included many established merchants with strong business connections throughout the Empire, as well as royal officials such as Thomas Hutchinson of Boston.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] In the mid-20th century, historian Leonard Woods Labaree identified eight characteristics of the Loyalists that made them essentially conservative, opposite to the characteristics of the Patriots.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Loyalists tended to feel that resistance to the Crown was morally wrong, while the Patriots thought that morality was on their side.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Loyalists were alienated when the Patriots resorted to violence, such as burning houses and tarring and feathering.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Many Loyalists wanted to take a centrist position and resisted the Patriots' demand to declare their opposition to the Crown.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Numerous Loyalists had maintained strong and long-standing relations with Britain, especially merchants in port cities such as New York and Boston.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Many Loyalists felt that independence was bound to come eventually, but they were fearful that revolution might lead to anarchy, tyranny, or mob rule.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] In contrast, the prevailing attitude among Patriots was a desire to seize the initiative.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Labaree also contended that Loyalists were pessimists who lacked the confidence in the future displayed by the Patriots.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] There were "tens of thousands" of Black Loyalists, enslaved African Americans who escaped to British lines and supported Britain's cause via several means.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Many of them died from disease, but the survivors were evacuated by the British to their remaining colonies in North America.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The revolution could divide families, such as William Franklin, son of Benjamin Franklin and royal governor of the Province of New Jersey who remained loyal to the Crown throughout the war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Recent immigrants who had not been fully Americanized were also inclined to support the King.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] After the war, the great majority of the half-million Loyalists remained in America and resumed normal lives.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Some became prominent American leaders, such as Samuel Seabury.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Approximately 46,000 Loyalists relocated to Canada; others moved to Britain (7,000), Florida, or the West Indies (9,000).
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The exiles represented approximately two percent of the total population of the colonies.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Nearly all Black Loyalists left for Nova Scotia, Florida, or England, where they could remain free.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Loyalists who left the South in 1783 took thousands of enslaved persons with them as they fled to the British West Indies.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] A minority of uncertain size tried to stay neutral in the war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Most kept a low profile, but the Quakers were the most important group to speak out for neutrality, especially in Pennsylvania.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The Quakers continued to do business with the British even after the war began, and they were accused of supporting British rule, "contrivers and authors of seditious publications" critical of the revolutionary cause.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Most Quakers remained neutral, although a sizeable number participated to some degree.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Women contributed to the American Revolution in many ways and were involved on both sides.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Formal politics did not include women, but ordinary domestic behaviors became charged with political significance as Patriot women confronted a war which permeated all aspects of political, civil, and domestic life.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] They participated by boycotting British goods, spying on the British, following armies as they marched, washing, cooking, and mending for soldiers, delivering secret messages, and even fighting disguised as men in a few cases, such as Deborah Samson.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Mercy Otis Warren held meetings in her house and cleverly attacked Loyalists with her creative plays and histories.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Many women also acted as nurses and helpers, tending to the soldiers' wounds and buying and selling goods for them.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Some of these camp followers even participated in combat, such as Madam John Turchin who led her husband's regiment into battle.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Above all, women continued the agricultural work at home to feed their families and the armies.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] They maintained their families during their husbands' absences and sometimes after their deaths.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] American women were integral to the success of the boycott of British goods, as the boycotted items were largely household articles such as tea and cloth.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Women had to return to knitting goods and to spinning and weaving their own cloth—skills that had fallen into disuse.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] In 1769, the women of Boston produced 40,000 skeins of yarn, and 180 women in Middletown, Massachusetts wove 20,522 yards (18,765 m) of cloth.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Many women gathered food, money, clothes, and other supplies during the war to help the soldiers.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] A woman's loyalty to her husband could become an open political act, especially for women in America committed to men who remained loyal to the King.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Legal divorce, usually rare, was granted to Patriot women whose husbands supported the King.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] In early 1776, France set up a major program of aid to the Americans, and the Spanish secretly added funds.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Each country spent one million "livres tournaises" to buy munitions.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] A dummy corporation run by Pierre Beaumarchais concealed their activities.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] American Patriots obtained some munitions from the Dutch Republic as well, through the French and Spanish ports in the West Indies.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Heavy expenditures and a weak taxation system pushed France toward bankruptcy.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] In 1777, Charles François Adrien le Paulmier, Chevalier d'Annemours, acting as a secret agent for France, made sure General George Washington was privy to his mission.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] He followed Congress around for the next two years, reporting what he observed back to France.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The Treaty of Alliance between the French and the Americans followed in 1778, which led to more French money, matériel and troops being sent to the United States.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Spain did not officially recognize the United States, but it was a French ally and it separately declared war on Britain on June 21, 1779.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Bernardo de Gálvez, general of the Spanish forces in New Spain bordering the Americans, also served as governor of Louisiana.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] He led an expedition of colonial troops to capture Florida from the British and to keep open a vital conduit for supplies going to the Americans.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Ethnic Germans served on both sides of the American Revolutionary War.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] As George III was also the Elector of Hanover, many supported the Loyalist cause and served as allies of the Kingdom of Great Britain; most notably rented auxiliary troops from German states such as the Landgraviate of Hessen-Kassel.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] American Patriots tended to represent such troops as mercenaries in propaganda against the British Crown.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Even American historians followed suit, in spite of Colonial-era jurists drawing a distinction between auxiliaries and mercenaries, with auxiliaries serving their prince when sent to the aid of another prince, and mercenaries serving a foreign prince as individuals.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] By this distinction the troops which served in the American Revolution were auxiliaries.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Other German individuals came to assist the American revolutionaries, most notably Friedrich Wilhelm von Steuben, who served as a general in the Continental Army and is credited with professionalizing that force, but most Germans who served were already colonists.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Von Steuben's native Prussia joined the League of Armed Neutrality, and King Frederick II of Prussia was well appreciated in the United States for his support early in the war.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] He expressed interest in opening trade with the United States and bypassing English ports, and allowed an American agent to buy arms in Prussia.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Frederick predicted American success, and promised to recognize the United States and American diplomats once France did the same.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Prussia also interfered in the recruiting efforts of Russia and neighboring German states when they raised armies to send to the Americas, and Frederick II forbade enlistment for the American war within Prussia.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] All Prussian roads were denied to troops from Anhalt-Zerbst, which delayed reinforcements that Howe had hoped to receive during the winter of 1777–1778.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] However, when the War of the Bavarian Succession (1778–1779) erupted, Frederick II became much more cautious with Prussian/British relations.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] U.S. ships were denied access to Prussian ports, and Frederick refused to officially recognize the United States until they had signed the Treaty of Paris.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Even after the war, Frederick II predicted that the United States was too large to operate as a republic, and that it would soon rejoin the British Empire with representatives in Parliament.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Most Indigenous people rejected pleas that they remain neutral and instead supported the British Crown.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The great majority of the ~200,000 indigenous people east of the Mississippi distrusted the Americans and supported the British cause, hoping to forestall continued expansion of settlement into their territories.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Those tribes closely involved in trade tended to side with the Patriots, although political factors were important as well.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Some tried to remain neutral, seeing little value in joining what they perceived to be a "white man's war", and fearing reprisals from whichever side they opposed.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The British did have other indigenous allies, particularly in the regions of southwest Quebec on the Patriot's frontier.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The British provided arms to Indigenous people who were led by Loyalists in war parties to raid frontier settlements from the Carolinas to New York.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] These war parties killed many settlers on the frontier, especially in western Pennsylvania and New York's Mohawk Valley.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] In 1776, Cherokee war parties attacked American settlers all along the southern Quebec frontier of the uplands throughout the Washington District, North Carolina (now Tennessee) and the Kentucky wilderness area.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The Chickamauga Cherokee under Tsiyu Gansini (*also* Dragging Canoe) allied themselves closely with the British, and fought on for an additional decade after the Treaty of Paris was signed.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] They launched raids with roughly 200 warriors, as seen in the Cherokee–American wars; they could not mobilize enough forces to invade settler areas without the help of allies, most often the Creek.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Joseph Brant (*also* Thayendanegea), from the powerful Mohawk tribe of the Haudenosaunee Confederacy, was the most prominent Indigenous leader against the Patriot forces.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] In 1778 and 1780, he led 300 Iroquois warriors and 100 white Loyalists in multiple attacks on small frontier settlements in New York and Pennsylvania, killing many settlers and destroying villages, crops, and food stockpiles.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] In 1779, the Continental Army forced the hostile Indigenous people out of upstate New York when Washington sent an army under John Sullivan which destroyed 40 evacuated Iroquois villages in central and western New York.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The Battle of Newtown proved decisive, as the Patriots had an advantage of three-to-one, and it ended significant resistance; there was little combat otherwise.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Facing starvation and homeless for the winter, the Iroquois that allied with the British fled to Canada.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] At the peace conference following the war, the British ceded indigenous lands without consultation with their allies that inhabited them.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] They transferred control to the United States of all the land south of the Great Lakes, east of the Mississippi, and north of Florida.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The existence of slavery in the American colonies had attracted criticism from both sides of the Atlantic as many could not reconcile the existence of the institution with the egalitarian ideals espoused by leaders of the Revolution.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The English writer Samuel Johnson wrote "how is it we hear the loudest yelps for liberty among the drivers of the Negroes?" in a text opposing the grievances of the colonists.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Crispus Attucks, of mixed racial heritage, was one of the five people killed in the Boston Massacre in 1770 and is considered the first American casualty for the cause of independence.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Free Blacks in the New England Colonies and Middle Colonies in the North as well as Southern Colonies fought on both sides of the War, but the majority fought for the Patriots.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Gary Nash reports that there were about 9,000 Black veteran Patriots, counting the Continental Army and Navy, state militia units, privateers, wagoneers in the Army, servants to officers, and spies.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The effects of the war were more dramatic in the South.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Tens of thousands of enslaved persons escaped to British lines throughout the South, causing dramatic losses to slaveholders and disrupting cultivation and harvesting of crops.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] For instance, South Carolina was estimated to have lost about 25,000 enslaved persons to flight, migration, or death which amounted to a third of its enslaved population.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] As noted by the historian Karen Cook Bell, during the Revolutionary War roughly one-third of all the escaped enslaved were women, even though prior to 1775 nearly 87% had been men.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] During the war, British commanders attempted to weaken the Patriots by issuing proclamations of freedom to their enslaved.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] In the November 1775 document known as Dunmore's Proclamation Virginia royal governor, Lord Dunmore recruited Black men for British military service with the promise of freedom, protection for their families, and land grants.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Hundreds of Black men responded and were formed into the Royal Ethiopian Regiment.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Colonists, primarily Southern Patriots, were deeply angered by Dunmore's proclamation, which spread through all of the Thirteen Colonies and threatened to upturn the existing American racial hierarchy; it also played a major role in Southern support for American independence.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Accusations that the British were encouraging slave rebellions were prominent features of Patriot propaganda, with Jefferson even accusing George III in the 27 colonial grievances of having "excited domestic Insurrections among us".
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] The 1779 Philipsburg Proclamation expanded the promise of freedom for Black men who enlisted in the British military to all the colonies in rebellion.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] At the conclusion of the war, British forces gave transportation to 10,000 of the formerly enslaved when they evacuated Savannah and Charles Town, carrying through on their promise.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] They evacuated and resettled more than 3,000 Black Loyalists from New York to Nova Scotia, Upper Canada, and Lower Canada.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Others sailed with the British to England or were resettled as freedmen in the West Indies of the Caribbean.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] But the enslaved carried to the Caribbean under control of Loyalist masters generally remained enslaved until the British abolition of slavery in its colonies in 1833–1838.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] More than 1,200 of the Black Loyalists of Nova Scotia later resettled in the British colony of Sierra Leone in Africa, where they became leaders of the Krio ethnic group of Freetown and the later national government.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Many of their descendants still live in Sierra Leone, as well as other African countries.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Despite the turmoil of the period, African-Americans contributed to the foundation of an American national identity during the Revolution.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p02] Phyllis Wheatley, an African American poet, popularized the image of Columbia to represent America.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] After the Revolution, genuinely democratic politics became possible in the former American colonies.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] The rights of the people were incorporated into state constitutions.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] Concepts of liberty, consent of the governed, individual rights, equality and due process under the law, and intolerance of corruption became incorporated as core values of liberal republicanism.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] The new United States government was empowered to undertake its own project of territorial expansion and settler colonialism.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] The greatest challenge to the old order in Europe was the challenge to inherited political power and the democratic idea that government rests on the consent of the governed.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] Losing the war and the Thirteen Colonies was a shock to Britain.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] The war revealed the limitations of Britain's fiscal-military state when they discovered that they suddenly faced powerful enemies with no allies, and they were dependent on extended and vulnerable transatlantic lines of communication.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] The defeat heightened dissension and escalated political antagonism to the king's ministers.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] The king went so far as to draft letters of abdication, although they were never delivered.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] Inside Parliament, the primary concern changed from fears of an over-mighty monarch to the issues of representation, parliamentary reform, and government retrenchment.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] Unable to accept loss of the war and the colonies as possibly due to anything else but widespread institutional corruption, reformers sought to root it out, and the result was a crisis from 1776 to 1783.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] The crisis ended after 1784 confidence in the British constitution was restored during the administration of Prime Minister William Pitt.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] The American Revolution ended an age of monarchy, and it began a new age of freedom.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] As a result of the growing wave started by the Revolution, there are now more people around the world living in freedom than ever before, both in absolute numbers and as a percentage of the world's population.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] Interpretations vary concerning the effect of the Revolution.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] Historians such as Bernard Bailyn, Gordon Wood, and Edmund Morgan view it as a unique and radical event which produced deep changes and had a profound effect on world affairs, such as an increasing belief in the principles of the Enlightenment.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] These were demonstrated by a leadership and government that espoused protection of natural rights, and a system of laws chosen by the people.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] John Murrin, by contrast, argues that the definition of "the people" at that time was mostly restricted to free men who passed a property qualification.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] The first shot of the American Revolution at the Battle of Lexington and Concord is referred to as the "shot heard 'round the world".
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] The American Revolution was the first of the Atlantic Revolutions: followed most notably by the French Revolution, the Haitian Revolution, and the Latin American wars of independence.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] Aftershocks contributed to rebellions in Ireland, the Polish–Lithuanian Commonwealth, and the Netherlands.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] Constitution, drafted shortly after independence, remains the world's oldest written constitution, and has been emulated by other countries, in some cases verbatim.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] Some historians and scholars argue that the subsequent wave of independence and revolutionary movements has contributed to the continued expansion of democratic government; 144 countries, representing two-third of the world's population, are full or partially democracies of some form.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] The Revolution had a strong, immediate influence in Great Britain, Ireland, the Netherlands, and France.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] Many British and Irish Whigs in Parliament spoke glowingly in favor of the American cause.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] In Ireland, the Protestant minority who controlled Ireland demanded self-rule.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] Under the leadership of Henry Grattan, the Irish Patriot Party forced the reversal of mercantilist prohibitions against trade with other British colonies.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] The King and his cabinet in London could not risk another rebellion, and so made a series of concessions to the Patriot faction in Dublin.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] Armed volunteer units of the *Protestant Ascendancy* were set up ostensibly to protect against an invasion from France.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] As had been in colonial America, so too in Ireland now the King no longer had a monopoly of lethal force.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] By 1798, the Irish were ready for a republican uprising.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] For many Europeans, such as the Marquis de Lafayette, who later were active during the era of the French Revolution, the American case along with the Dutch Revolt (end of the 16th century) and the 17th century English Civil War, was among the examples of overthrowing an old regime.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] The American Declaration of Independence influenced the French Declaration of the Rights of Man and of the Citizen of 1789.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] The spirit of the Declaration of Independence led to laws ending slavery in all the Northern states and the Northwest Territory, with New Jersey the last in 1804.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] States such as New Jersey and New York adopted gradual emancipation, which kept some people as slaves for more than two decades longer.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] During the revolution, the contradiction between the Patriots' professed ideals of liberty and the institution of slavery generated increased scrutiny of the latter.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] As early as 1764, the Boston Patriot leader James Otis, Jr. declared that all men, "white or black", were "by the law of nature" born free.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] Anti-slavery calls became more common in the early 1770s.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] In 1773, Benjamin Rush, the future signer of the Declaration of Independence, called on "advocates for American liberty" to oppose slavery.
[src:greenwood-cemetery-philadelphia/american-revolution-p03] Slavery became an issue that had to be addressed.
